window.MM['ent_p2_nasopharynx']=[
  {q:"The muscles of facial expression are derived embryologically from the:",o:["Second pharyngeal arch","First pharyngeal arch","Third pharyngeal arch","Fourth pharyngeal arch","Occipital somites"],a:0,e:"Second pharyngeal arch fits the embryologic origin of muscles of facial expression; characteristic innervation by facial nerve accompanies this development. Facial movements develop clinically from these muscles.<br><br>Standard embryology: mesoderm of the second branchial arch differentiates into mimetic musculature symptomatically. Associated nerve supply remains cranial nerve VII.<br><br>First arch (option B) forms muscles of mastication; third and fourth arches (options C and D) form pharyngeal structures; occipital somites (option E) contribute tongue muscles. Therefore facial muscles arise from second arch.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The sensory nerve supply of the face is mainly through the:",o:["Trigeminal nerve","Glossopharyngeal nerve","Facial nerve","Hypoglossal nerve","Vagus nerve"],a:0,e:"Trigeminal nerve fits the principal sensory innervation of facial skin; characteristic division into ophthalmic, maxillary, and mandibular branches. Facial sensation develops clinically through these pathways.<br><br>Standard anatomy: trigeminal sensory fibers transmit pain, touch, and temperature from facial structures symptomatically. Corneal reflex also depends on trigeminal input.<br><br>Facial nerve (option C) mainly supplies facial muscles; glossopharyngeal (option B), hypoglossal (option D), and vagus nerves (option E) do not provide major facial sensation. Therefore trigeminal nerve predominates.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"The facial artery is a branch of the:",o:["External carotid artery","Vertebral artery","Internal carotid artery","Subclavian artery","Maxillary artery"],a:0,e:"External carotid artery fits the origin of facial artery; characteristic tortuous facial course supplying superficial structures. Facial bleeding develops clinically after trauma.<br><br>Standard anatomy: facial artery arises in neck and crosses mandible near masseter anterior border symptomatically. Extensive anastomoses exist with opposite side vessels.<br><br>Internal carotid (option C), vertebral artery (option B), subclavian artery (option D), and maxillary artery (option E) do not directly give rise to facial artery. Therefore external carotid is correct.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The danger area of face is mainly dangerous because of communication with:",o:["Cavernous sinus","Submandibular gland","Middle ear","Internal jugular vein only","Thyroid gland"],a:0,e:"Cavernous sinus fits the major intracranial structure connected with danger area of face; characteristic valveless venous communication permits spread of infection. Cavernous sinus thrombosis develops clinically severely.<br><br>Standard anatomy: facial veins communicate with ophthalmic veins and pterygoid plexus symptomatically. Absence of venous valves facilitates retrograde spread.<br><br>Submandibular gland (option B), middle ear (option C), internal jugular vein alone (option D), and thyroid gland (option E) are not primary concerns. Therefore cavernous sinus spread is dangerous.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"The muscle responsible for closure of eyelids is:",o:["Orbicularis oculi","Corrugator supercilii","Levator palpebrae superioris","Procerus","Frontalis"],a:0,e:"Orbicularis oculi fits the principal muscle closing eyelids; characteristic circular arrangement around orbital opening. Lagophthalmos develops clinically after facial nerve palsy.<br><br>Standard anatomy: facial nerve innervates orbicularis oculi enabling blinking and corneal protection symptomatically. Weakness predisposes corneal ulceration.<br><br>Levator palpebrae (option C) elevates eyelid; corrugator supercilii (option B) wrinkles forehead; procerus (option D) affects nasal bridge; frontalis (option E) elevates eyebrows. Therefore orbicularis oculi closes eyelids.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"The parotid gland is traversed by all EXCEPT:",o:["Facial nerve","External carotid artery","Retromandibular vein","Hypoglossal nerve","Parotid lymphatics"],a:3,e:"Hypoglossal nerve fits the structure not traversing parotid gland; characteristic tongue motor course beneath digastric muscle. Tongue deviation develops clinically after injury.<br><br>Standard anatomy: facial nerve divides within parotid gland alongside external carotid artery and retromandibular vein symptomatically. Surgical anatomy remains clinically important.<br><br>Facial nerve (option A), external carotid artery (option B), retromandibular vein (option C), and lymphatics (option E) pass through gland substance. Therefore hypoglossal nerve does not.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The facial vein communicates with the cavernous sinus through the:",o:["Lingual vein","Superior ophthalmic vein","External jugular vein","Inferior thyroid vein","Vertebral vein"],a:1,e:"Superior ophthalmic vein fits the communication pathway between facial vein and cavernous sinus; characteristic route for spread of facial infections. Intracranial complications develop clinically rarely but seriously.<br><br>Standard anatomy: angular vein communicates with ophthalmic venous channels symptomatically. Absence of venous valves allows retrograde flow.<br><br>Lingual vein (option A), external jugular vein (option C), inferior thyroid vein (option D), and vertebral vein (option E) lack direct communication. Therefore superior ophthalmic vein forms the pathway.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"The main motor nerve supply of facial muscles is through the:",o:["Facial nerve","Trigeminal nerve","Glossopharyngeal nerve","Accessory nerve","Hypoglossal nerve"],a:0,e:"Facial nerve fits the principal motor supply of muscles of facial expression; characteristic branching within parotid gland. Facial asymmetry develops clinically after palsy.<br><br>Standard anatomy: cranial nerve VII exits stylomastoid foramen before dividing into terminal branches symptomatically. It controls voluntary facial movements.<br><br>Trigeminal nerve (option B) supplies mastication muscles; glossopharyngeal (option C), accessory (option D), and hypoglossal nerves (option E) have different motor functions. Therefore facial nerve innervates facial muscles.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The muscle known as the \"smiling muscle\" is:",o:["Buccinator","Masseter","Zygomaticus major","Temporalis","Risorius only"],a:2,e:"Zygomaticus major fits the \"smiling muscle\"; characteristic elevation of mouth angle during facial expression. Facial weakness develops clinically after nerve paralysis.<br><br>Standard anatomy: zygomaticus major extends from zygomatic bone toward mouth angle symptomatically. Facial nerve supplies its motor activity.<br><br>Buccinator (option A) compresses cheek; masseter (option B) elevates mandible; temporalis (option D) assists mastication; risorius (option E) retracts mouth angle weakly. Therefore zygomaticus major primarily produces smiling.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"The sensory innervation of cheek skin is mainly by the:",o:["Maxillary nerve","Ophthalmic nerve","Facial nerve","Glossopharyngeal nerve","Accessory nerve"],a:0,e:"Maxillary nerve fits the principal sensory supply of cheek skin; characteristic trigeminal distribution through infraorbital branches. Facial numbness develops clinically after injury.<br><br>Standard anatomy: maxillary division exits skull through foramen rotundum symptomatically. Infraorbital nerve supplies midfacial sensation.<br><br>Ophthalmic nerve (option B) supplies forehead; facial nerve (option C) is mainly motor; glossopharyngeal (option D) and accessory nerves (option E) do not innervate cheek skin. Therefore maxillary nerve predominates.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"The facial nerve exits skull through the:",o:["Stylomastoid foramen","Foramen ovale","Jugular foramen","Foramen spinosum","Hypoglossal canal"],a:0,e:"Stylomastoid foramen fits the extracranial exit of facial nerve; characteristic location between mastoid and styloid processes. Facial paralysis develops clinically after injury.<br><br>Standard anatomy: facial nerve traverses temporal bone before emerging through stylomastoid foramen symptomatically. It then enters parotid gland.<br><br>Jugular foramen (option C), foramen ovale (option B), foramen spinosum (option D), and hypoglossal canal (option E) transmit different neurovascular structures. Therefore facial nerve exits via stylomastoid foramen.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The buccinator muscle is pierced by the:",o:["Facial artery","Parotid duct","Facial vein","External carotid artery","Lingual artery"],a:1,e:"Parotid duct fits the structure piercing buccinator muscle; characteristic opening opposite upper second molar tooth. Saliva enters oral cavity clinically through this route.<br><br>Standard anatomy: Stensen duct crosses masseter then turns medially through buccinator symptomatically. Obstruction may cause parotid swelling.<br><br>Facial artery (option A), facial vein (option C), external carotid artery (option D), and lingual artery (option E) do not pierce buccinator. Therefore parotid duct traverses muscle.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"The blood supply of scalp is rich mainly because vessels:",o:["Lie in dense connective tissue","Are valveless arteries","Lack smooth muscle","Arise only from internal carotid","Contain lymphatics"],a:0,e:"Dense connective tissue fixation fits the reason scalp vessels bleed profusely; characteristic inability of vessels to retract after injury. Severe hemorrhage develops clinically from scalp wounds.<br><br>Standard anatomy: vascular walls remain tethered within fibrous connective tissue symptomatically. Rich arterial anastomoses additionally contribute.<br><br>Lack of smooth muscle (option C), valveless arteries (option B), exclusive internal carotid origin (option D), and lymphatic content (option E) are inaccurate explanations. Therefore connective tissue fixation explains bleeding.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"The branch of facial nerve supplying frontalis muscle is the:",o:["Buccal branch","Cervical branch","Temporal branch","Marginal mandibular branch","Zygomatic branch"],a:2,e:"Temporal branch fits the facial nerve division supplying frontalis muscle; characteristic forehead wrinkling function. Brow drooping develops clinically after injury.<br><br>Standard anatomy: temporal branch ascends superiorly across zygomatic arch symptomatically. It also innervates orbicularis oculi upper fibers.<br><br>Buccal branch (option A), cervical branch (option B), marginal mandibular branch (option D), and zygomatic branch (option E) supply other facial regions. Therefore temporal branch innervates frontalis.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The main function of buccinator muscle is:",o:["Compress cheek during mastication","Close eyelids","Elevate mandible","Depress lower lip","Wrinkle forehead"],a:0,e:"Buccinator muscle fits cheek compression during mastication; characteristic prevention of food accumulation within vestibule. Facial weakness develops clinically after facial nerve palsy.<br><br>Standard physiology: buccinator assists chewing and blowing actions symptomatically. It is supplied by buccal branch of facial nerve.<br><br>Closing eyelids (option B), elevating mandible (option C), depressing lower lip (option D), and wrinkling forehead (option E) are functions of different muscles. Therefore buccinator compresses cheek.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"The facial artery crosses the mandible at the anterior border of:",o:["Masseter","Buccinator","Temporalis","Medial pterygoid","Digastric posterior belly"],a:0,e:"Masseter anterior border fits the landmark where facial artery crosses mandible; characteristic palpable arterial pulsation. Facial trauma may injure this vessel clinically.<br><br>Standard anatomy: tortuous facial artery ascends toward angle of mouth and nose symptomatically. Surface anatomy remains surgically important.<br><br>Temporalis (option C), buccinator (option B), medial pterygoid (option D), and digastric muscle (option E) are inaccurate landmarks. Therefore artery crosses near masseter anterior border.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The sensory nerve supplying lower lip is mainly the:",o:["Mental nerve","Infraorbital nerve","Supraorbital nerve","Facial nerve","Auriculotemporal nerve"],a:0,e:"Mental nerve fits the principal sensory supply of lower lip; characteristic terminal branch of inferior alveolar nerve. Lip numbness develops clinically after mandibular injury.<br><br>Standard anatomy: mental nerve exits mandible through mental foramen symptomatically. It supplies chin and lower lip sensation.<br><br>Infraorbital nerve (option B) supplies upper lip; supraorbital nerve (option C) supplies forehead; facial nerve (option D) is mainly motor; auriculotemporal nerve (option E) supplies temporal region. Therefore mental nerve innervates lower lip.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"The occipitofrontalis muscle consists of frontal and occipital bellies connected by:",o:["Epicranial aponeurosis","Superficial fascia","Temporal fascia","Deep cervical fascia","Buccopharyngeal fascia"],a:0,e:"Epicranial aponeurosis fits the connection between frontal and occipital bellies of occipitofrontalis muscle; characteristic scalp mobility function. Forehead wrinkling develops clinically through this muscle.<br><br>Standard anatomy: galea aponeurotica forms a strong tendinous sheet across skull vault symptomatically. Scalp lacerations may gape widely when cut transversely.<br><br>Temporal fascia (option C), superficial fascia (option B), deep cervical fascia (option D), and buccopharyngeal fascia (option E) do not connect muscle bellies. Therefore epicranial aponeurosis is correct.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"The venous drainage of face mainly ends in the:",o:["Internal jugular vein","External jugular vein only","Subclavian vein","Vertebral vein","Azygos vein"],a:0,e:"Internal jugular vein fits the main terminal drainage pathway of facial veins; characteristic continuation through common facial vein. Venous spread of infection develops clinically through these channels.<br><br>Standard anatomy: facial venous blood ultimately reaches internal jugular circulation symptomatically. Communications with cavernous sinus remain clinically important.<br><br>External jugular vein only (option B), subclavian vein (option C), vertebral vein (option D), and azygos vein (option E) are not primary drainage endpoints. Therefore facial veins mainly drain into internal jugular vein.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The marginal mandibular branch of facial nerve supplies muscles of:",o:["Forehead","Nose","Lower lip","Eyelids","Auricle only"],a:2,e:"Marginal mandibular branch fits motor supply of lower lip muscles; characteristic depression and asymmetry after injury. Smiling difficulty develops clinically frequently.<br><br>Standard anatomy: this branch courses along lower mandibular border symptomatically. Surgical injury during submandibular operations is important clinically.<br><br>Forehead (option A), nose (option B), eyelids (option D), and auricle only (option E) receive supply from different branches. Therefore marginal mandibular branch controls lower lip muscles.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"The trigeminal ganglion lies in:",o:["Cavernous sinus","Meckel's cave","Internal acoustic meatus","Jugular foramen","Optic canal"],a:1,e:"Meckel's cave fits the location of trigeminal ganglion; characteristic sensory ganglion of cranial nerve V. Facial pain syndromes develop clinically from trigeminal pathology.<br><br>Standard anatomy: trigeminal ganglion lies within a dural recess in middle cranial fossa symptomatically. Three major sensory divisions arise from it.<br><br>Cavernous sinus (option A), internal acoustic meatus (option C), jugular foramen (option D), and optic canal (option E) do not contain trigeminal ganglion. Therefore Meckel's cave is correct.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"The frontalis muscle primarily functions to:",o:["Elevate eyebrows","Close mouth","Compress cheek","Depress mandible","Elevate upper lip only"],a:0,e:"Frontalis muscle fits eyebrow elevation and forehead wrinkling; characteristic expression of surprise. Forehead asymmetry develops clinically in facial nerve palsy.<br><br>Standard anatomy: frontalis forms the frontal belly of occipitofrontalis muscle symptomatically. Temporal branch of facial nerve supplies it.<br><br>Closing mouth (option B), cheek compression (option C), mandibular depression (option D), and isolated upper lip elevation (option E) are unrelated functions. Therefore frontalis elevates eyebrows.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The facial nerve divides within the:",o:["Parotid gland","Thyroid gland","Submandibular gland","Lacrimal gland","Sublingual gland"],a:0,e:"Parotid gland fits the site where facial nerve divides into terminal branches; characteristic \"pes anserinus\" arrangement. Facial paralysis develops clinically after parotid surgery injury.<br><br>Standard anatomy: nerve branches traverse gland substance without supplying secretomotor fibers to parotid symptomatically. Surgical anatomy remains critically important.<br><br>Submandibular gland (option C), thyroid gland (option B), lacrimal gland (option D), and sublingual gland (option E) are incorrect locations. Therefore facial nerve divides within parotid gland.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"The artery accompanying the infraorbital nerve is the:",o:["Infraorbital artery","Facial artery","Lingual artery","Maxillary artery only","Ophthalmic artery only"],a:0,e:"Infraorbital artery fits the vessel accompanying infraorbital nerve through infraorbital canal; characteristic supply to midfacial structures. Facial trauma may injure this bundle clinically.<br><br>Standard anatomy: infraorbital artery arises from maxillary artery and exits infraorbital foramen symptomatically. It supplies cheek and upper lip regions.<br><br>Facial artery (option B), lingual artery (option C), isolated maxillary artery only (option D), and ophthalmic artery only (option E) are inaccurate. Therefore infraorbital artery accompanies nerve.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"The platysma muscle is supplied by the:",o:["Cervical branch of facial nerve","Buccal branch of facial nerve","Temporal branch of facial nerve","Hypoglossal nerve","Mandibular nerve"],a:0,e:"Cervical branch of facial nerve fits the motor supply of platysma muscle; characteristic superficial neck muscle action. Neck skin tightening develops clinically through platysma contraction.<br><br>Standard anatomy: platysma extends from upper chest toward mandible symptomatically. It belongs to muscles of facial expression.<br><br>Temporal branch (option C), buccal branch (option B), hypoglossal nerve (option D), and mandibular nerve (option E) do not primarily supply platysma. Therefore cervical branch innervates this muscle.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A 24-year-old woman develops inability to close her right eye after parotid surgery. On examination, forehead wrinkling is absent and angle of mouth deviates to opposite side. The injured nerve is most likely:",o:["Trigeminal nerve","Facial nerve","Glossopharyngeal nerve","Hypoglossal nerve","Accessory nerve"],a:1,e:"Facial nerve injury fits complete ipsilateral facial paralysis following parotid surgery; characteristic involvement of forehead, eyelids, and mouth angle. Lagophthalmos develops clinically prominently.<br><br>Standard anatomy: facial nerve divides within parotid gland into terminal branches vulnerable during gland surgery symptomatically. Corneal ulceration may follow incomplete eyelid closure.<br><br>Trigeminal nerve (option A), glossopharyngeal nerve (option C), hypoglossal nerve (option D), and accessory nerve (option E) do not produce complete facial muscle paralysis. Therefore facial nerve damage is responsible.<br><br><em>(Recall and Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient develops cavernous sinus thrombosis after squeezing a furuncle over upper lip. The spread occurred through:",o:["Facial vein and superior ophthalmic vein","External jugular vein only","Inferior thyroid vein","Lingual vein","Subclavian vein"],a:0,e:"Facial vein and superior ophthalmic vein fit the route of intracranial spread from danger area of face. Fever and ophthalmoplegia develop clinically in cavernous sinus thrombosis.<br><br>Standard anatomy: valveless venous channels allow retrograde spread of septic emboli symptomatically. Angular vein communication remains especially important.<br><br>External jugular vein only (option B), inferior thyroid vein (option C), lingual vein (option D), and subclavian vein (option E) do not directly connect to cavernous sinus. Therefore facial and ophthalmic veins are involved.<br><br><em>(Recall and Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient cannot whistle or blow air effectively after facial trauma. Which muscle is most likely paralyzed?",o:["Temporalis","Masseter","Buccinator","Platysma","Frontalis"],a:2,e:"Buccinator paralysis fits inability to whistle or blow air effectively; characteristic loss of cheek compression during oral activity. Food accumulation develops clinically within oral vestibule.<br><br>Standard anatomy: buccinator muscle is supplied by buccal branches of facial nerve symptomatically. It assists mastication and facial expression.<br><br>Temporalis (option A) and masseter (option B) elevate mandible; platysma (option D) tightens neck skin; frontalis (option E) wrinkles forehead. Therefore buccinator dysfunction explains symptoms.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with mandibular fracture develops numbness over lower lip and chin. Which nerve is likely injured?",o:["Infraorbital nerve","Mental nerve","Facial nerve","Supraorbital nerve","Auriculotemporal nerve"],a:1,e:"Mental nerve injury fits numbness involving lower lip and chin after mandibular fracture. Sensory loss develops clinically over mental region.<br><br>Standard anatomy: mental nerve emerges from mental foramen as terminal branch of inferior alveolar nerve symptomatically. Mandibular trauma commonly affects it.<br><br>Infraorbital nerve (option A) supplies upper lip; facial nerve (option C) is mainly motor; supraorbital nerve (option D) supplies forehead; auriculotemporal nerve (option E) supplies temporal skin. Therefore mental nerve is injured.<br><br><em>(Recall and Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The facial artery can be palpated at the lower border of mandible just anterior to the:",o:["Masseter muscle","Medial pterygoid","Temporalis muscle","Digastric anterior belly","Buccinator muscle"],a:0,e:"Masseter anterior border fits the landmark for facial artery palpation at mandibular margin. Arterial pulsation develops clinically palpable at this site.<br><br>Standard anatomy: tortuous facial artery crosses mandible before ascending toward nose and mouth symptomatically. Surface anatomy is surgically important.<br><br>Temporalis (option C), medial pterygoid (option B), digastric muscle (option D), and buccinator (option E) are inaccurate landmarks. Therefore facial artery crosses near masseter.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with Bell palsy develops excessive tearing from right eye. The main reason is:",o:["Increased lacrimal secretion","Obstruction of nasolacrimal duct","Paralysis of trigeminal nerve","Failure of eyelid closure","Optic nerve lesion"],a:3,e:"Failure of eyelid closure fits epiphora in Bell palsy because lacrimal drainage requires normal blinking. Corneal dryness develops clinically additionally.<br><br>Standard physiology: orbicularis oculi paralysis impairs tear distribution and lacrimal pump mechanism symptomatically. Tears overflow despite reduced drainage.<br><br>Increased lacrimal secretion (option A), nasolacrimal obstruction (option B), trigeminal paralysis (option C), and optic nerve lesions (option E) are not primary causes. Therefore incomplete blinking explains tearing.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 62-year-old diabetic presents with severe facial pain over cheek and absent corneal reflex on same side. The affected trigeminal division is most likely:",o:["Ophthalmic division","Maxillary division","Mandibular division","Facial nerve","Glossopharyngeal nerve"],a:0,e:"Ophthalmic division involvement fits absent corneal reflex because afferent sensation from cornea travels through V1 fibers. Facial pain develops clinically over forehead and orbit.<br><br>Standard neuroanatomy: nasociliary branch of ophthalmic nerve supplies corneal sensation symptomatically. Loss predisposes corneal injury.<br><br>Maxillary division (option B) supplies cheek; mandibular division (option C) supplies lower jaw; facial nerve (option D) carries efferent blink response; glossopharyngeal nerve (option E) is unrelated. Therefore ophthalmic division is involved.<br><br><em>(Recall and Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A child with facial laceration near angle of mouth develops drooling and inability to elevate upper lip. Which branch of facial nerve is injured?",o:["Temporal branch","Zygomatic branch","Cervical branch","Buccal branch","Posterior auricular branch"],a:3,e:"Buccal branch injury fits weakness around upper lip and mouth angle after facial trauma. Oral incompetence develops clinically during eating.<br><br>Standard anatomy: buccal branches innervate buccinator and upper lip muscles symptomatically. Midfacial expression becomes asymmetrical.<br><br>Temporal branch (option A) supplies forehead; zygomatic branch (option B) supplies orbicularis oculi; cervical branch (option C) supplies platysma; posterior auricular branch (option E) supplies occipital muscles. Therefore buccal branch is injured.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The most dangerous area of face extends from:",o:["Nose to forehead only","Corners of mouth to bridge of nose","Chin to angle of mandible","Zygoma to temporal region","Forehead to scalp vertex"],a:1,e:"Corners of mouth to bridge of nose fit the danger area of face; characteristic venous communication with cavernous sinus. Intracranial infection develops clinically rarely but severely.<br><br>Standard anatomy: facial and angular veins lack valves allowing retrograde septic spread symptomatically. Manipulation of infected lesions increases risk.<br><br>Nose to forehead (option A), chin to mandible (option C), zygoma to temporal region (option D), and scalp vertex (option E) are inaccurate boundaries. Therefore central midface forms danger area.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient develops inability to wrinkle forehead after temporal bone fracture. The affected nerve branch is:",o:["Buccal branch","Marginal mandibular branch","Temporal branch","Cervical branch","Mental nerve"],a:2,e:"Temporal branch injury fits inability to wrinkle forehead because it supplies frontalis muscle. Brow ptosis develops clinically on affected side.<br><br>Standard anatomy: temporal branch ascends superficially over zygomatic arch symptomatically. Trauma may damage this branch.<br><br>Buccal branch (option A) supplies cheek muscles; marginal mandibular branch (option B) supplies lower lip; cervical branch (option D) supplies platysma; mental nerve (option E) is sensory. Therefore temporal branch is affected.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"The infraorbital nerve is a branch of the:",o:["Maxillary nerve","Ophthalmic nerve","Mandibular nerve","Facial nerve","Vagus nerve"],a:0,e:"Maxillary nerve fits the origin of infraorbital nerve; characteristic sensory supply to cheek, upper lip, and lower eyelid. Midface numbness develops clinically after injury.<br><br>Standard anatomy: infraorbital nerve traverses infraorbital canal and exits infraorbital foramen symptomatically. It represents continuation of maxillary division.<br><br>Ophthalmic nerve (option B), mandibular nerve (option C), facial nerve (option D), and vagus nerve (option E) do not give rise to infraorbital nerve. Therefore maxillary division is correct.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with parotid malignancy develops complete ipsilateral facial paralysis. This finding suggests:",o:["Benign tumor","Facial nerve involvement","Trigeminal neuralgia","Middle ear disease","Glossopharyngeal lesion"],a:1,e:"Facial nerve involvement fits complete facial paralysis in parotid malignancy; characteristic sign of aggressive invasive disease. Poor prognosis develops clinically frequently.<br><br>Standard pathology: malignant tumors infiltrate nerve fibers within gland substance symptomatically. Benign parotid lesions rarely cause facial palsy.<br><br>Benign tumor (option A), trigeminal neuralgia (option C), middle ear disease (option D), and glossopharyngeal lesions (option E) do not explain complete facial weakness. Therefore facial nerve infiltration is likely.<br><br><em>(Recall and Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"The venous drainage of scalp eventually reaches the:",o:["Internal jugular vein","Portal vein","Inferior vena cava directly","Azygos vein","Pulmonary vein"],a:0,e:"Internal jugular vein fits the major venous drainage pathway of scalp. Scalp infections may spread clinically through emissary venous channels.<br><br>Standard anatomy: superficial scalp veins communicate with intracranial venous sinuses symptomatically. Valveless connections remain clinically important.<br><br>Portal vein (option B), direct inferior vena cava drainage (option C), azygos vein (option D), and pulmonary vein (option E) are incorrect pathways. Therefore scalp veins drain mainly into internal jugular system.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A knife injury just below angle of mandible causes weakness of lower lip depression. Which nerve branch is damaged?",o:["Buccal branch","Zygomatic branch","Temporal branch","Marginal mandibular branch","Great auricular nerve"],a:3,e:"Marginal mandibular branch injury fits weakness of lower lip depression after mandibular trauma. Facial asymmetry develops clinically during smiling.<br><br>Standard anatomy: this branch courses superficially near inferior mandibular border symptomatically. Surgical procedures in submandibular region risk injury.<br><br>Buccal branch (option A) affects upper lip; zygomatic branch (option B) affects eyelids; temporal branch (option C) affects forehead; great auricular nerve (option E) is sensory. Therefore marginal mandibular branch is involved.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The principal arterial supply of face is from the:",o:["Internal carotid artery","External carotid artery","Vertebral artery","Ophthalmic artery only","Basilar artery"],a:1,e:"External carotid artery fits the principal arterial supply of face through facial and maxillary branches. Facial hemorrhage develops clinically after trauma.<br><br>Standard anatomy: extensive vascular anastomoses maintain rich facial blood supply symptomatically. Facial artery remains especially important.<br><br>Internal carotid artery (option A), vertebral artery (option C), isolated ophthalmic artery (option D), and basilar artery (option E) contribute less prominently. Therefore external carotid predominates.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with facial palsy cannot retain food between teeth and cheek. Paralysis of which muscle explains this?",o:["Temporalis","Masseter","Orbicularis oris","Buccinator","Frontalis"],a:3,e:"Buccinator paralysis fits food accumulation between teeth and cheek during mastication. Oral incompetence develops clinically in facial nerve palsy.<br><br>Standard physiology: buccinator compresses cheek against teeth to maintain food positioning symptomatically. Weakness impairs chewing efficiency.<br><br>Temporalis (option A) and masseter (option B) elevate mandible; orbicularis oris (option C) closes lips; frontalis (option E) wrinkles forehead. Therefore buccinator dysfunction explains symptoms.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"The sensory innervation of forehead skin is mainly through the:",o:["Mental nerve","Infraorbital nerve","Supraorbital nerve","Buccal nerve","Facial nerve"],a:2,e:"Supraorbital nerve fits the principal sensory supply of forehead skin; characteristic branch of ophthalmic division of trigeminal nerve. Forehead numbness develops clinically after injury.<br><br>Standard anatomy: supraorbital nerve exits through supraorbital notch symptomatically. It supplies anterior scalp and forehead.<br><br>Mental nerve (option A) supplies chin; infraorbital nerve (option B) supplies cheek; buccal nerve (option D) supplies oral mucosa; facial nerve (option E) is mainly motor. Therefore supraorbital nerve innervates forehead.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient develops corneal ulceration after Bell palsy primarily because of paralysis of:",o:["Orbicularis oculi","Frontalis","Buccinator","Platysma","Zygomaticus major"],a:0,e:"Orbicularis oculi paralysis fits corneal ulceration after Bell palsy because eyelid closure becomes incomplete. Exposure keratitis develops clinically prominently.<br><br>Standard physiology: blinking spreads tears across corneal surface symptomatically. Loss of corneal protection predisposes ulcer formation.<br><br>Frontalis (option B), buccinator (option C), platysma (option D), and zygomaticus major (option E) do not directly protect cornea. Therefore orbicularis oculi dysfunction causes ulceration.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The facial nerve enters parotid gland after emerging from the:",o:["Foramen ovale","Jugular foramen","Carotid canal","Stylomastoid foramen","Hypoglossal canal"],a:3,e:"Stylomastoid foramen fits the extracranial exit point of facial nerve before parotid entry. Facial weakness develops clinically after injury near this region.<br><br>Standard anatomy: nerve exits temporal bone then traverses parotid gland symptomatically. Branching occurs within gland substance.<br><br>Foramen ovale (option A), jugular foramen (option B), carotid canal (option C), and hypoglossal canal (option E) transmit other structures. Therefore facial nerve emerges through stylomastoid foramen.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with trigeminal neuralgia involving maxillary division most likely experiences pain over the:",o:["Forehead","Lower jaw","Occipital scalp","Cheek and upper lip","Neck"],a:3,e:"Cheek and upper lip pain fit trigeminal neuralgia involving maxillary division. Sharp electric shock-like episodes develop clinically characteristically.<br><br>Standard neuroanatomy: maxillary nerve supplies midfacial sensory territory symptomatically. Trigger zones may precipitate attacks.<br><br>Forehead (option A) belongs ophthalmic division; lower jaw (option B) belongs mandibular division; occipital scalp (option C) and neck (option E) are unrelated territories. Therefore maxillary pain involves cheek and upper lip.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"The muscle primarily responsible for pursing lips is:",o:["Orbicularis oris","Buccinator","Masseter","Platysma","Risorius"],a:0,e:"Orbicularis oris fits the principal muscle responsible for lip pursing and closure. Speech articulation develops clinically through coordinated lip movement.<br><br>Standard anatomy: orbicularis oris surrounds oral opening symptomatically. Facial nerve supplies its motor function.<br><br>Buccinator (option B) compresses cheek; masseter (option C) elevates mandible; platysma (option D) tightens neck skin; risorius (option E) retracts mouth angle. Therefore orbicularis oris purses lips.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A deep facial infection spreads to cavernous sinus mainly because facial veins are:",o:["Thick walled","Surrounded by fascia","Valveless","Arterialized","End arteries"],a:2,e:"Valveless facial veins fit retrograde spread of facial infection into cavernous sinus. Cavernous sinus thrombosis develops clinically with fever and ophthalmoplegia.<br><br>Standard anatomy: absence of venous valves allows bidirectional blood flow symptomatically. Central facial infections remain clinically dangerous.<br><br>Thick vessel walls (option A), fascial surroundings (option B), arterialization (option D), and end-artery status (option E) are incorrect explanations. Therefore valveless veins permit spread.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with facial trauma loses sensation over lower eyelid and lateral nose. Which nerve is injured?",o:["Supraorbital nerve","Mental nerve","Buccal branch facial nerve","Infraorbital nerve","Auriculotemporal nerve"],a:3,e:"Infraorbital nerve injury fits sensory loss over lower eyelid, lateral nose, and upper lip. Midface numbness develops clinically after orbital fractures.<br><br>Standard anatomy: infraorbital nerve exits infraorbital foramen symptomatically. It represents continuation of maxillary division.<br><br>Supraorbital nerve (option A) supplies forehead; mental nerve (option B) supplies chin; facial nerve branch (option C) is motor; auriculotemporal nerve (option E) supplies temporal region. Therefore infraorbital nerve is injured.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"The \"pes anserinus\" in parotid gland refers to:",o:["Facial nerve branching pattern","Venous plexus","Arterial arcade","Lymphatic drainage","Muscle attachment"],a:0,e:"Facial nerve branching pattern fits the \"pes anserinus\" within parotid gland; characteristic goose-foot arrangement of terminal branches. Surgical injury develops clinically during parotidectomy.<br><br>Standard anatomy: temporal, zygomatic, buccal, mandibular, and cervical branches radiate within gland symptomatically. Preservation remains surgically crucial.<br><br>Venous plexus (option B), arterial arcade (option C), lymphatic drainage (option D), and muscle attachment (option E) are unrelated. Therefore pes anserinus describes facial nerve branching.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with facial nerve palsy complains that food spills from affected side while eating. The primary cause is weakness of:",o:["Temporalis muscle","Masseter muscle","Medial pterygoid","Orbicularis oris","Digastric muscle"],a:3,e:"Orbicularis oris weakness fits drooling and food spillage from affected side during eating. Oral incompetence develops clinically in facial palsy.<br><br>Standard physiology: orbicularis oris maintains lip seal during mastication and swallowing symptomatically. Facial nerve injury disrupts this function.<br><br>Temporalis (option A), masseter (option B), medial pterygoid (option C), and digastric muscle (option E) mainly influence mandibular movement rather than lip closure. Therefore orbicularis oris weakness explains spillage.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"The adenoids are situated in the:",o:["Oropharynx","Hypopharynx","Nasopharynx","Laryngopharynx","Oral cavity"],a:2,e:"Nasopharynx fits the anatomical location of adenoids; characteristic lymphoid tissue on roof and posterior wall. Mouth breathing develops clinically after hypertrophy.<br><br>Standard anatomy: adenoids form part of Waldeyer's lymphatic ring symptomatically. Enlargement commonly affects pediatric airway patency.<br><br>Oropharynx (option A), hypopharynx (option B), laryngopharynx (option D), and oral cavity (option E) do not contain adenoids. Therefore adenoids lie within nasopharynx.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"Adenoids are derived embryologically from the:",o:["First pharyngeal pouch","Second pharyngeal pouch","Third pharyngeal pouch","Nasopharyngeal mucosa-associated lymphoid tissue","Neural crest cells"],a:3,e:"Nasopharyngeal mucosa-associated lymphoid tissue fits the developmental origin of adenoids; characteristic immune defense role within upper airway. Hypertrophy develops clinically during childhood.<br><br>Standard histology: lymphoid follicles proliferate beneath respiratory epithelium symptomatically. Antigen exposure stimulates enlargement.<br><br>First pouch (option A), second pouch (option B), third pouch (option C), and neural crest cells (option E) do not directly form adenoids. Therefore adenoids arise from mucosal lymphoid tissue.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"The epithelial lining of adenoids is mainly:",o:["Keratinized squamous epithelium","Nonkeratinized squamous epithelium","Transitional epithelium","Pseudostratified ciliated columnar epithelium","Simple cuboidal epithelium"],a:3,e:"Pseudostratified ciliated columnar epithelium fits the respiratory lining of adenoids; characteristic mucociliary clearance function. Chronic infection develops clinically after persistent inflammation.<br><br>Standard histology: respiratory epithelium overlies lymphoid follicles within nasopharynx symptomatically. Goblet cells contribute mucus production.<br><br>Keratinized squamous (option A), nonkeratinized squamous (option B), transitional (option C), and cuboidal epithelium (option E) are inappropriate linings. Therefore respiratory epithelium predominates.<br><br><em>(Wheater's Functional Histology)</em>"},
  {q:"The blood supply of adenoids is mainly from branches of the:",o:["Internal carotid artery","Facial artery","Vertebral artery","Ascending pharyngeal artery","Lingual artery"],a:3,e:"Ascending pharyngeal artery fits the principal blood supply of adenoids; characteristic branch of external carotid circulation. Post-adenoidectomy bleeding develops clinically occasionally.<br><br>Standard anatomy: ascending pharyngeal vessels supply nasopharyngeal mucosa and lymphoid tissue symptomatically. Additional small contributions may exist.<br><br>Internal carotid artery (option A), facial artery (option B), vertebral artery (option C), and lingual artery (option E) are less significant sources. Therefore ascending pharyngeal artery predominates.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The maximum physiological enlargement of adenoids usually occurs around the age of:",o:["Birth","2 years","Puberty","5-7 years","Old age"],a:3,e:"Five to seven years fits the period of maximum physiological adenoid enlargement; characteristic active childhood lymphoid proliferation. Nasal obstruction develops clinically commonly.<br><br>Standard physiology: repeated antigenic stimulation enlarges adenoidal tissue symptomatically. Regression usually begins after puberty.<br><br>Birth (option A), two years (option B), puberty (option C), and old age (option E) do not represent peak hypertrophy periods. Therefore adenoids enlarge maximally around early school age.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common symptom of adenoid hypertrophy is:",o:["Epistaxis","Nasal obstruction","Dysphagia","Tinnitus","Vertigo"],a:1,e:"Nasal obstruction fits the most common symptom of adenoid hypertrophy; characteristic mouth breathing and snoring develop clinically. Sleep disturbance occurs frequently.<br><br>Standard pathology: enlarged adenoidal tissue obstructs posterior choanae symptomatically. Chronic obstruction may affect facial growth.<br><br>Epistaxis (option A), dysphagia (option C), tinnitus (option D), and vertigo (option E) are less characteristic symptoms. Therefore nasal obstruction predominates.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"Adenoid facies typically includes all EXCEPT:",o:["Open mouth","Pinched nose","High arched palate","Prominent chin","Dull facial expression"],a:3,e:"Prominent chin does not fit classical adenoid facies; characteristic features include open-mouth posture and elongated face. Chronic mouth breathing develops clinically prominently.<br><br>Standard pathology: persistent nasal obstruction alters maxillofacial growth patterns symptomatically. High-arched palate and dental malocclusion commonly occur.<br><br>Open mouth (option A), pinched nose (option B), high-arched palate (option C), and dull expression (option E) are classic findings. Therefore prominent chin is not typical.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The commonest complication of adenoid hypertrophy is:",o:["Otitis media with effusion","Acute mastoiditis","Facial palsy","Labyrinthitis","Tonsillar abscess"],a:0,e:"Otitis media with effusion fits the commonest complication of adenoid hypertrophy; characteristic Eustachian tube obstruction causes middle ear ventilation failure. Conductive hearing loss develops clinically commonly.<br><br>Standard pathology: enlarged adenoids obstruct tubal openings within nasopharynx symptomatically. Negative middle ear pressure promotes fluid accumulation.<br><br>Acute mastoiditis (option B), facial palsy (option C), labyrinthitis (option D), and tonsillar abscess (option E) occur less frequently. Therefore glue ear remains the commonest complication.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A child with persistent mouth breathing, snoring, and recurrent glue ear most likely has:",o:["Allergic rhinitis only","Adenoid hypertrophy","Nasal polyp","Choanal atresia","Deviated nasal septum"],a:1,e:"Adenoid hypertrophy fits mouth breathing, snoring, and recurrent otitis media with effusion in children. Conductive hearing loss develops clinically frequently.<br><br>Standard pathology: enlarged adenoids obstruct choanae and Eustachian tube openings symptomatically. Sleep-disordered breathing may occur additionally.<br><br>Allergic rhinitis alone (option A), nasal polyp (option C), choanal atresia (option D), and deviated septum (option E) less commonly explain this combined presentation. Therefore adenoid hypertrophy is likely.<br><br><em>(Recall and Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The investigation most useful for assessing adenoid hypertrophy is:",o:["Pure tone audiometry only","X-ray mastoid","Lateral nasopharyngeal X-ray","CT brain","Tympanoplasty"],a:2,e:"Lateral nasopharyngeal X-ray fits a useful investigation for evaluating adenoid size and choanal obstruction. Mouth breathing develops clinically with enlargement.<br><br>Standard radiology: soft tissue shadow in nasopharynx can be assessed symptomatically. Endoscopy may provide more direct visualization.<br><br>Pure tone audiometry (option A), mastoid X-ray (option B), CT brain (option D), and tympanoplasty (option E) do not directly evaluate adenoids. Therefore lateral nasopharyngeal radiograph is useful.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"The most accurate method for evaluating adenoid size is:",o:["Anterior rhinoscopy","Posterior rhinoscopy only","X-ray skull","Nasal endoscopy","MRI orbit"],a:3,e:"Nasal endoscopy fits the most accurate method for direct adenoid evaluation; characteristic visualization of choanal obstruction and Eustachian tube relation. Mouth breathing develops clinically prominently.<br><br>Standard ENT examination: flexible or rigid endoscopy provides dynamic assessment symptomatically. Degree of hypertrophy becomes directly observable.<br><br>Anterior rhinoscopy (option A), posterior rhinoscopy alone (option B), skull X-ray (option C), and MRI orbit (option E) are less precise. Therefore nasal endoscopy remains superior.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The adenoids are part of:",o:["Waldeyer's ring","Circle of Willis","Kiesselbach plexus","Pterygopalatine ganglion","Cavernous sinus"],a:0,e:"Waldeyer's ring fits the lymphoid ring containing adenoids; characteristic immune defense function at upper aerodigestive tract entrance. Recurrent infections develop clinically in childhood.<br><br>Standard anatomy: adenoids, palatine tonsils, tubal tonsils, and lingual tonsils compose this ring symptomatically. Mucosal immunity remains important.<br><br>Circle of Willis (option B), Kiesselbach plexus (option C), pterygopalatine ganglion (option D), and cavernous sinus (option E) are unrelated structures. Therefore adenoids belong to Waldeyer's ring.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A child with adenoid hypertrophy commonly speaks with:",o:["Hoarse voice","Hypernasal speech","Whispering voice","Hyponasal speech","Staccato speech"],a:3,e:"Hyponasal speech fits adenoid hypertrophy because nasopharyngeal obstruction reduces nasal resonance. Mouth breathing develops clinically concurrently.<br><br>Standard physiology: blocked nasal airflow alters resonance during speech production symptomatically. Enlarged adenoids reduce nasopharyngeal patency.<br><br>Hoarse voice (option A), hypernasal speech (option B), whispering voice (option C), and staccato speech (option E) are less characteristic. Therefore hyponasality predominates.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"The Eustachian tube opens into the nasopharynx at the level of the:",o:["Hard palate","Torus tubarius","Inferior turbinate","Pyriform fossa","Cricoid cartilage"],a:1,e:"Torus tubarius fits the nasopharyngeal opening site of Eustachian tube; characteristic elevation formed by tubal cartilage. Middle ear ventilation develops clinically through this pathway.<br><br>Standard anatomy: enlarged adenoids near torus tubarius may obstruct tubal opening symptomatically. Otitis media with effusion commonly follows.<br><br>Hard palate (option A), inferior turbinate (option C), pyriform fossa (option D), and cricoid cartilage (option E) are unrelated locations. Therefore Eustachian tube opens near torus tubarius.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"The commonest age group requiring adenoidectomy is:",o:["Neonates","Adolescents","Children","Elderly adults","Middle-aged adults"],a:2,e:"Children fit the commonest age group requiring adenoidectomy; characteristic adenoid hypertrophy peaks during childhood. Mouth breathing develops clinically frequently.<br><br>Standard pathology: recurrent infections and obstructive symptoms become significant before puberty symptomatically. Adenoids usually regress later.<br><br>Neonates (option A), adolescents (option B), elderly adults (option D), and middle-aged adults (option E) less commonly require surgery. Therefore childhood remains the typical age group.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A child with enlarged adenoids is most likely to develop which facial deformity?",o:["Saddle nose","Hemifacial microsomia","Cleft lip","Adenoid facies","Prognathism only"],a:3,e:"Adenoid facies fits chronic adenoid hypertrophy causing prolonged mouth breathing and altered facial growth. Dental malocclusion develops clinically commonly.<br><br>Standard pathology: persistent nasal obstruction changes maxillofacial skeletal development symptomatically. High-arched palate frequently accompanies findings.<br><br>Saddle nose (option A), cleft lip (option C), hemifacial microsomia (option B), and isolated prognathism (option E) are unrelated deformities. Therefore adenoid facies develops characteristically.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"The adenoids usually regress after:",o:["Birth","Infancy","Adulthood","Puberty","Old age"],a:3,e:"Puberty fits the period after which adenoids physiologically regress; characteristic decline in lymphoid tissue activity occurs. Nasal obstruction improves clinically afterward.<br><br>Standard physiology: decreasing antigenic stimulation and lymphoid involution reduce adenoid size symptomatically. Adult hypertrophy remains uncommon.<br><br>Birth (option A), infancy (option B), adulthood (option C), and old age (option E) are inaccurate timelines. Therefore adenoids regress after puberty.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common hearing loss associated with adenoid hypertrophy is:",o:["Sensorineural hearing loss","Central hearing loss","Mixed hearing loss","Conductive hearing loss","Psychogenic deafness"],a:3,e:"Conductive hearing loss fits adenoid hypertrophy because Eustachian tube obstruction produces middle ear effusion. Speech delay develops clinically in severe pediatric cases.<br><br>Standard pathology: negative middle ear pressure impairs ossicular sound transmission symptomatically. Tympanic membrane retraction may coexist.<br><br>Sensorineural loss (option A), mixed loss (option C), central hearing loss (option B), and psychogenic deafness (option E) are less characteristic. Therefore conductive loss predominates.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"The lymphatic drainage of adenoids mainly goes to:",o:["Submental nodes","Retropharyngeal nodes","Occipital nodes","Preauricular nodes","Axillary nodes"],a:1,e:"Retropharyngeal nodes fit the principal lymphatic drainage of adenoids; characteristic location behind pharyngeal wall. Infection spread develops clinically in children.<br><br>Standard anatomy: nasopharyngeal lymphatics drain posteriorly toward retropharyngeal nodal chains symptomatically. These nodes regress with age.<br><br>Submental nodes (option A), occipital nodes (option C), preauricular nodes (option D), and axillary nodes (option E) do not primarily drain adenoids. Therefore retropharyngeal nodes are correct.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common indication for adenoidectomy is:",o:["Epistaxis","Nasopharyngeal carcinoma","Facial palsy","Obstructive adenoid hypertrophy","Septal hematoma"],a:3,e:"Obstructive adenoid hypertrophy fits the commonest indication for adenoidectomy; characteristic mouth breathing and sleep disturbance occur clinically. Otitis media may coexist.<br><br>Standard ENT practice: surgery is considered when airway obstruction or recurrent ear disease becomes significant symptomatically. Growth and behavior may improve afterward.<br><br>Epistaxis (option A), nasopharyngeal carcinoma (option B), facial palsy (option C), and septal hematoma (option E) are unrelated indications. Therefore obstruction remains the main reason.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The most serious complication after adenoidectomy is:",o:["Dental caries","Secondary hemorrhage","Velopharyngeal insufficiency","Otitis externa","Tinnitus"],a:2,e:"Velopharyngeal insufficiency fits a serious complication after adenoidectomy, especially in occult cleft palate. Hypernasal speech develops clinically prominently.<br><br>Standard pathology: removal of adenoid tissue may expose inadequate palatal closure mechanisms symptomatically. Nasal regurgitation can occur additionally.<br><br>Dental caries (option A), secondary hemorrhage (option B), otitis externa (option D), and tinnitus (option E) are less severe or unrelated complications. Therefore velopharyngeal insufficiency is important.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"The adenoids receive sensory innervation mainly from the:",o:["Facial nerve","Glossopharyngeal nerve","Hypoglossal nerve","Vagus nerve","Maxillary nerve"],a:4,e:"Maxillary nerve fits the principal sensory innervation of adenoids through nasopharyngeal branches. Referred symptoms develop clinically occasionally.<br><br>Standard anatomy: pharyngeal branches from pterygopalatine ganglion-associated fibers supply nasopharyngeal mucosa symptomatically. Sensory input contributes to reflexes.<br><br>Facial nerve (option A), glossopharyngeal nerve (option B), vagus nerve (option D), and hypoglossal nerve (option C) are less directly involved. Therefore maxillary division contributes most significantly.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"Persistent adenoid hypertrophy in adults should raise suspicion of:",o:["Physiological enlargement","Allergic conjunctivitis","Acute rhinitis only","Nasopharyngeal malignancy","Otosclerosis"],a:3,e:"Nasopharyngeal malignancy fits persistent adult adenoid hypertrophy because normal adenoids regress after puberty. Nasal obstruction develops clinically progressively.<br><br>Standard ENT practice: unilateral symptoms, epistaxis, or neck nodes require careful evaluation symptomatically. Biopsy may become necessary.<br><br>Physiological enlargement (option A), acute rhinitis only (option C), allergic conjunctivitis (option B), and otosclerosis (option E) do not explain persistent adult masses. Therefore malignancy suspicion is important.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The instrument commonly used for adenoidectomy is the:",o:["Tilley forceps","Luc forceps","Ballenger swivel knife","Walsham forceps","St. Clair Thompson adenoid curette"],a:4,e:"St. Clair Thompson adenoid curette fits the classic instrument used for adenoidectomy. Nasopharyngeal obstruction improves clinically after tissue removal.<br><br>Standard surgical technique: curettage removes hypertrophied lymphoid tissue from nasopharyngeal roof symptomatically. Hemostasis remains important postoperatively.<br><br>Tilley forceps (option A), Luc forceps (option B), Walsham forceps (option D), and Ballenger knife (option C) are used for different ENT procedures. Therefore adenoid curette is standard.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A child with adenoid hypertrophy and glue ear most likely shows which tympanometry finding?",o:["Type A tympanogram","Type As tympanogram","Type B tympanogram","Type Ad tympanogram","Type C only"],a:2,e:"Type B tympanogram fits otitis media with effusion associated with adenoid hypertrophy. Conductive hearing loss develops clinically commonly.<br><br>Standard audiology: middle ear fluid reduces tympanic membrane mobility producing a flat tympanometric curve symptomatically. Eustachian tube dysfunction underlies pathology.<br><br>Type A (option A) represents normal findings; Type As (option B) suggests stiffness; Type Ad (option D) suggests hypermobility; isolated Type C (option E) indicates negative pressure without effusion. Therefore Type B is typical.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A 6-year-old child presents with persistent mouth breathing, snoring, restless sleep, and recurrent ear infections. Otoscopy shows bilateral dull tympanic membranes with air-fluid levels. The most likely underlying cause is:",o:["Deviated nasal septum","Allergic rhinitis","Adenoid hypertrophy","Choanal polyp","Acute sinusitis"],a:2,e:"Adenoid hypertrophy fits persistent mouth breathing with recurrent otitis media with effusion in children. Conductive hearing loss develops clinically commonly.<br><br>Standard pathology: enlarged adenoids obstruct Eustachian tube openings and posterior choanae symptomatically. Middle ear ventilation becomes impaired.<br><br>Deviated septum (option A), allergic rhinitis (option B), choanal polyp (option D), and acute sinusitis (option E) less commonly produce this combined presentation. Therefore adenoid hypertrophy remains most likely.<br><br><em>(Recall and Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The adenoids are best visualized by:",o:["Anterior rhinoscopy","Indirect laryngoscopy","Plain X-ray skull","Otoscopy","Nasal endoscopy"],a:4,e:"Nasal endoscopy fits the best direct visualization method for adenoids; characteristic assessment of size and choanal obstruction becomes possible. Nasal blockage develops clinically in hypertrophy.<br><br>Standard ENT examination: flexible or rigid endoscopy allows detailed nasopharyngeal evaluation symptomatically. Tubal openings may also be inspected.<br><br>Anterior rhinoscopy (option A), indirect laryngoscopy (option B), otoscopy (option D), and skull X-ray (option C) are less accurate. Therefore nasal endoscopy remains superior.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A child with adenoid facies is most likely to have:",o:["Cleft palate","Chronic mouth breathing","Facial nerve palsy","Acute epiglottitis","Nasal trauma"],a:1,e:"Chronic mouth breathing fits the development of adenoid facies; characteristic elongated face and high-arched palate develop gradually. Sleep disturbance occurs clinically frequently.<br><br>Standard pathology: persistent nasal obstruction alters craniofacial skeletal growth symptomatically. Dental malocclusion commonly accompanies findings.<br><br>Cleft palate (option A), facial palsy (option C), acute epiglottitis (option D), and nasal trauma (option E) do not directly cause adenoid facies. Therefore chronic mouth breathing is responsible.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The adenoids form the superior part of:",o:["Circle of Willis","Cavernous sinus","Kiesselbach plexus","Waldeyer's ring","Pterygoid plexus"],a:3,e:"Waldeyer's ring fits the lymphoid ring containing adenoids superiorly; characteristic immune barrier function occurs at upper airway entrance. Recurrent infections develop clinically in children.<br><br>Standard anatomy: adenoids, tonsils, and lingual lymphoid tissue collectively form this defensive ring symptomatically. Antigen exposure stimulates growth.<br><br>Circle of Willis (option A), Kiesselbach plexus (option C), cavernous sinus (option B), and pterygoid plexus (option E) are unrelated structures. Therefore adenoids belong to Waldeyer's ring.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A 5-year-old child snores loudly, stops breathing intermittently during sleep, and remains sleepy during daytime. The most likely diagnosis is:",o:["Acute laryngitis","Allergic rhinitis","Adenoid hypertrophy causing obstructive sleep apnea","Foreign body aspiration","Epiglottitis"],a:2,e:"Adenoid hypertrophy causing obstructive sleep apnea fits snoring with witnessed apneic episodes and daytime somnolence. Behavioral problems develop clinically in severe disease.<br><br>Standard pathology: enlarged adenoids obstruct upper airway during sleep symptomatically. Hypoxia and fragmented sleep may impair growth.<br><br>Acute laryngitis (option A), allergic rhinitis (option B), foreign body aspiration (option D), and epiglottitis (option E) less commonly cause chronic sleep apnea. Therefore adenoid obstruction is likely.<br><br><em>(Recall and Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common bacterial organism isolated from infected adenoids is:",o:["Mycobacterium tuberculosis","Clostridium tetani","Vibrio cholerae","Streptococcus pneumoniae","Corynebacterium diphtheriae"],a:3,e:"Streptococcus pneumoniae fits a common organism isolated from chronically infected adenoids; characteristic recurrent upper airway infections occur clinically. Otitis media frequently coexists.<br><br>Standard microbiology: bacterial colonization within hypertrophied lymphoid tissue perpetuates inflammation symptomatically. Mixed flora may also be present.<br><br>Tuberculosis (option A), Vibrio cholerae (option C), Clostridium tetani (option B), and Corynebacterium diphtheriae (option E) are uncommon causes. Therefore pneumococcus commonly predominates.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A child with adenoid hypertrophy commonly has which type of voice?",o:["Hoarse voice","Breathy voice","Whispering speech","Hypernasal voice","Hyponasal voice"],a:4,e:"Hyponasal voice fits adenoid hypertrophy because posterior nasal airway obstruction decreases nasal resonance. Mouth breathing develops clinically concurrently.<br><br>Standard physiology: reduced airflow through nasal cavity alters speech resonance symptomatically. Enlarged adenoids obstruct nasopharyngeal passage.<br><br>Hoarse voice (option A), breathy voice (option B), hypernasal voice (option D), and whispering speech (option C) are less characteristic. Therefore hyponasality predominates.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A child with recurrent glue ear secondary to adenoid hypertrophy most likely demonstrates:",o:["Sensorineural hearing loss","Conductive hearing loss","Mixed hearing loss","Central deafness","Presbycusis"],a:1,e:"Conductive hearing loss fits glue ear secondary to adenoid hypertrophy; characteristic middle ear effusion impairs ossicular sound conduction. Speech delay develops clinically in severe cases.<br><br>Standard pathology: Eustachian tube obstruction produces negative middle ear pressure and fluid accumulation symptomatically. Tympanic membrane mobility decreases.<br><br>Sensorineural loss (option A), mixed loss (option C), central deafness (option D), and presbycusis (option E) are less typical. Therefore conductive loss predominates.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common radiological investigation for adenoid hypertrophy is:",o:["CT orbit","MRI brain","Orthopantomogram","Water's view X-ray","Lateral nasopharyngeal X-ray"],a:4,e:"Lateral nasopharyngeal X-ray fits the classic radiologic investigation for adenoid hypertrophy. Choanal narrowing develops clinically with enlargement.<br><br>Standard radiology: adenoid shadow and airway obstruction can be assessed symptomatically. Imaging complements endoscopic findings.<br><br>CT orbit (option A), MRI brain (option B), Water's view X-ray (option D), and orthopantomogram (option C) are not standard investigations. Therefore lateral nasopharyngeal radiograph remains useful.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 7-year-old child has chronic mouth breathing, dull facial expression, crowded teeth, and high-arched palate. The diagnosis is:",o:["Cushing syndrome","Pierre Robin sequence","Adenoid facies","Bell palsy","Treacher Collins syndrome"],a:2,e:"Adenoid facies fits chronic mouth breathing with elongated dull face and dental malocclusion. Nasal obstruction develops clinically from enlarged adenoids.<br><br>Standard pathology: persistent oral breathing alters facial skeletal growth and palatal architecture symptomatically. Orthodontic abnormalities commonly occur.<br><br>Cushing syndrome (option A), Pierre Robin sequence (option B), Bell palsy (option D), and Treacher Collins syndrome (option E) produce different craniofacial abnormalities. Therefore adenoid facies is correct.<br><br><em>(Recall and Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common reason for recurrent otitis media in adenoid hypertrophy is:",o:["Tympanic membrane perforation","Facial nerve palsy","Eustachian tube obstruction","Cochlear damage","Otosclerosis"],a:2,e:"Eustachian tube obstruction fits recurrent otitis media associated with adenoid hypertrophy; characteristic middle ear ventilation failure occurs clinically. Conductive deafness develops frequently.<br><br>Standard pathology: enlarged adenoids block tubal openings near torus tubarius symptomatically. Secretions accumulate behind tympanic membrane.<br><br>Tympanic membrane perforation (option A), facial palsy (option B), cochlear damage (option D), and otosclerosis (option E) are unrelated mechanisms. Therefore tubal obstruction is responsible.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"The adenoids receive their main arterial supply from the:",o:["Lingual artery","Vertebral artery","Internal maxillary artery only","Ascending pharyngeal artery","Internal carotid artery"],a:3,e:"Ascending pharyngeal artery fits the principal blood supply of adenoids; characteristic nasopharyngeal vascular distribution develops anatomically. Postoperative bleeding occurs clinically occasionally.<br><br>Standard anatomy: branches from external carotid circulation nourish adenoidal tissue symptomatically. Vascularity contributes to intraoperative hemorrhage risk.<br><br>Lingual artery (option A), isolated internal maxillary artery only (option C), vertebral artery (option B), and internal carotid artery (option E) are less significant sources. Therefore ascending pharyngeal artery predominates.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A child undergoes adenoidectomy and later develops hypernasal speech with nasal regurgitation. The complication is:",o:["Facial palsy","Velopharyngeal insufficiency","Choanal atresia","Septal hematoma","Epistaxis"],a:1,e:"Velopharyngeal insufficiency fits hypernasal speech and nasal regurgitation after adenoidectomy. Speech abnormality develops clinically especially in occult cleft palate patients.<br><br>Standard pathology: removal of adenoidal tissue exposes inadequate palatal closure mechanisms symptomatically. Nasopharyngeal seal becomes incomplete.<br><br>Facial palsy (option A), choanal atresia (option C), septal hematoma (option D), and epistaxis (option E) do not explain persistent hypernasality. Therefore velopharyngeal insufficiency is responsible.<br><br><em>(Recall and Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"Persistent adenoid enlargement in an adult should raise suspicion for:",o:["Physiological hypertrophy","Allergic conjunctivitis","Acute rhinitis","Nasopharyngeal carcinoma","Vocal cord polyp"],a:3,e:"Nasopharyngeal carcinoma fits persistent adult adenoid enlargement because adenoids normally regress after puberty. Neck nodes develop clinically commonly.<br><br>Standard ENT practice: unilateral symptoms, epistaxis, or persistent obstruction require biopsy symptomatically. Adult adenoid hypertrophy is abnormal.<br><br>Physiological hypertrophy (option A), acute rhinitis (option C), allergic conjunctivitis (option B), and vocal cord polyp (option E) do not explain persistent masses. Therefore malignancy suspicion is important.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A child with adenoid hypertrophy most commonly sleeps in which manner?",o:["Mouth closed and silent","Mouth open with snoring","Sitting upright always","Lateral decubitus without snoring","Prone with stridor"],a:1,e:"Mouth-open sleeping with snoring fits adenoid hypertrophy because nasal airway obstruction forces oral respiration. Restless sleep develops clinically frequently.<br><br>Standard pathology: enlarged adenoids narrow nasopharyngeal airway symptomatically. Sleep-disordered breathing commonly follows.<br><br>Silent sleep (option A), constant upright posture (option C), lateral decubitus without snoring (option D), and prone stridorous breathing (option E) are less typical. Therefore mouth-open snoring predominates.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common age at which adenoids regress significantly is after:",o:["2 years","5 years","Infancy","40 years","Puberty"],a:4,e:"Puberty fits the stage after which adenoids undergo physiological involution; characteristic reduction in lymphoid activity occurs clinically. Nasal obstruction improves afterward.<br><br>Standard physiology: declining immune stimulation decreases adenoid size symptomatically. Adult hypertrophy remains unusual.<br><br>Two years (option A), five years (option B), forty years (option D), and infancy (option C) are inaccurate timelines. Therefore regression mainly follows puberty.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A child with recurrent adenoid infection may complain of referred pain to the:",o:["Chest","Abdomen","Shoulder","Ear","Eye"],a:3,e:"Ear pain fits referred otalgia from adenoid inflammation because of shared nasopharyngeal neural pathways. Conductive hearing issues develop clinically additionally.<br><br>Standard anatomy: glossopharyngeal and pharyngeal sensory pathways contribute to referred symptoms symptomatically. Eustachian tube dysfunction commonly coexists.<br><br>Chest (option A), shoulder (option C), abdomen (option B), and eye (option E) are not common referral sites. Therefore ear pain may occur.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"The adenoids are covered by which epithelium?",o:["Stratified keratinized squamous epithelium","Transitional epithelium","Cuboidal epithelium","Simple squamous epithelium","Pseudostratified ciliated columnar epithelium"],a:4,e:"Pseudostratified ciliated columnar epithelium fits the respiratory mucosal lining of adenoids. Chronic inflammation develops clinically after repeated infections.<br><br>Standard histology: ciliated respiratory epithelium overlies lymphoid follicles symptomatically. Goblet cells participate in mucus production.<br><br>Keratinized squamous (option A), transitional (option B), simple squamous (option D), and cuboidal epithelium (option C) are inappropriate. Therefore respiratory epithelium lines adenoids.<br><br><em>(Wheater's Functional Histology)</em>"},
  {q:"A child with enlarged adenoids and persistent hearing loss most likely has which tympanogram?",o:["Type A","Type Ad","Type B","Type As","Type D"],a:2,e:"Type B tympanogram fits middle ear effusion associated with adenoid hypertrophy. Conductive hearing loss develops clinically commonly.<br><br>Standard audiology: fluid-filled middle ear reduces tympanic membrane mobility producing a flat tracing symptomatically. Eustachian tube dysfunction underlies pathology.<br><br>Type A (option A) is normal; Type Ad (option B) indicates hypermobility; Type As (option D) indicates stiffness; Type D (option E) is not standard classification. Therefore Type B is expected.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The classic surgical instrument for adenoidectomy is:",o:["Luc forceps","Tilley forceps","Freer elevator","Walsham forceps","St. Clair Thompson adenoid curette"],a:4,e:"St. Clair Thompson adenoid curette fits the standard instrument used in conventional adenoidectomy. Airway obstruction improves clinically after successful removal.<br><br>Standard surgical technique: curettage removes lymphoid tissue from nasopharyngeal roof symptomatically. Hemostasis must be secured carefully.<br><br>Luc forceps (option A), Tilley forceps (option B), Walsham forceps (option D), and Freer elevator (option C) are intended for other ENT procedures. Therefore adenoid curette is correct.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 4-year-old child presents with chronic rhinorrhea, snoring, mouth breathing, and poor school performance. Examination reveals dull tympanic membranes bilaterally. Which management is most appropriate?",o:["Septoplasty only","Oral antihistamines only","Adenoidectomy with assessment for grommets","Mastoidectomy","Cochlear implantation"],a:2,e:"Adenoidectomy with possible grommet insertion fits chronic adenoid hypertrophy complicated by glue ear and hearing impairment. Poor school performance develops clinically from conductive deafness.<br><br>Standard management: removal of obstructive adenoids improves airway and Eustachian tube function symptomatically. Ventilation tubes may restore hearing.<br><br>Septoplasty (option A), antihistamines alone (option B), mastoidectomy (option D), and cochlear implantation (option E) are inappropriate. Therefore adenoid surgery with ear management is indicated.<br><br><em>(Recall and Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common nasopharyngeal structure obstructed by enlarged adenoids is the:",o:["Posterior choanae","Pyriform fossa","Vallecula","External auditory canal","Oral cavity"],a:0,e:"Posterior choanae fit the primary structures obstructed by enlarged adenoids; characteristic nasal blockage and mouth breathing develop clinically. Snoring commonly accompanies symptoms.<br><br>Standard anatomy: adenoids enlarge from roof and posterior wall of nasopharynx symptomatically. Choanal narrowing impairs nasal airflow.<br><br>Pyriform fossa (option B), vallecula (option C), external auditory canal (option D), and oral cavity (option E) are unrelated structures. Therefore posterior choanae become obstructed.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A child with severe adenoid hypertrophy may develop pulmonary hypertension due to prolonged:",o:["Epistaxis","Conductive deafness","Vertigo","Dysphagia","Hypoxia"],a:4,e:"Hypoxia fits pulmonary hypertension secondary to severe obstructive adenoid hypertrophy. Sleep apnea develops clinically in advanced cases.<br><br>Standard pathology: chronic upper airway obstruction produces intermittent hypoxemia and increased pulmonary vascular resistance symptomatically. Cor pulmonale may eventually occur.<br><br>Epistaxis (option A), conductive deafness (option B), dysphagia (option D), and vertigo (option C) do not produce pulmonary hypertension. Therefore chronic hypoxia is responsible.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"The adenoids are located on the:",o:["Floor of nasopharynx","Base of tongue","Lateral wall of oropharynx","Roof and posterior wall of nasopharynx","Anterior nasal septum"],a:3,e:"Roof and posterior wall of nasopharynx fit the anatomical location of adenoids. Nasal obstruction develops clinically after hypertrophy.<br><br>Standard anatomy: adenoidal lymphoid tissue occupies superior nasopharyngeal region symptomatically. Enlargement may obstruct choanae and Eustachian tube openings.<br><br>Floor of nasopharynx (option A), lateral oropharyngeal wall (option C), tongue base (option B), and anterior septum (option E) are incorrect locations. Therefore adenoids occupy roof and posterior wall.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The most frequent indication for combining adenoidectomy with grommet insertion is:",o:["Sensorineural deafness","Chronic suppurative otitis media","Otitis media with effusion","Otosclerosis","Ménière disease"],a:2,e:"Otitis media with effusion fits the commonest indication for adenoidectomy combined with grommet insertion. Conductive hearing loss develops clinically prominently.<br><br>Standard pathology: adenoid hypertrophy obstructs Eustachian tube causing persistent middle ear fluid symptomatically. Ventilation tubes restore aeration.<br><br>Sensorineural deafness (option A), chronic suppurative otitis media (option B), otosclerosis (option D), and Ménière disease (option E) are unrelated indications. Therefore glue ear most commonly requires combined treatment.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common malignant tumor of the nasopharynx repeatedly recalled in FCPS and JCAT is:",o:["Squamous cell carcinoma","Adenocarcinoma","Lymphoma","Fibrosarcoma","Melanoma"],a:0,e:"Squamous cell carcinoma fits the commonest malignant tumor of nasopharynx; characteristic presentation with cervical lymphadenopathy develops clinically early. Nasal obstruction frequently coexists.<br><br>Standard pathology: malignant transformation of nasopharyngeal epithelium occurs near fossa of Rosenmüller symptomatically. Epstein-Barr virus association remains important.<br><br>Adenocarcinoma (option B), lymphoma (option C), fibrosarcoma (option D), and melanoma (option E) occur less frequently. Therefore squamous carcinoma predominates.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common site of origin of nasopharyngeal carcinoma is:",o:["Roof of nasopharynx","Posterior choana","Posterior nasal septum","Soft palate","Fossa of Rosenmüller"],a:4,e:"Fossa of Rosenmüller fits the commonest site of origin for nasopharyngeal carcinoma; characteristic lateral nasopharyngeal recess location. Neck node metastasis develops clinically early.<br><br>Standard anatomy: rich lymphatic drainage near pharyngeal recess promotes cervical spread symptomatically. Tumors may remain hidden initially.<br><br>Roof of nasopharynx (option A), posterior choana (option B), soft palate (option D), and posterior septum (option C) are less common origins. Therefore Rosenmüller fossa predominates.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 45-year-old man presents with unilateral serous otitis media, nasal obstruction, and neck node enlargement. The diagnosis should be considered as:",o:["Allergic rhinitis","Nasopharyngeal carcinoma","Juvenile angiofibroma","Adenoid hypertrophy","Antrochoanal polyp"],a:1,e:"Nasopharyngeal carcinoma fits unilateral serous otitis media with cervical lymphadenopathy in adults. Nasal obstruction develops clinically progressively.<br><br>Standard pathology: tumor near Eustachian tube opening obstructs middle ear ventilation symptomatically. Cervical metastases commonly precede primary symptoms.<br><br>Allergic rhinitis (option A), juvenile angiofibroma (option C), adenoid hypertrophy (option D), and antrochoanal polyp (option E) less commonly produce this triad. Therefore nasopharyngeal carcinoma must be suspected.<br><br><em>(Recall and Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The virus strongly associated with nasopharyngeal carcinoma is:",o:["HPV","Epstein-Barr virus","Cytomegalovirus","Herpes simplex virus","Influenza virus"],a:1,e:"Epstein-Barr virus fits the strongest viral association with nasopharyngeal carcinoma; characteristic undifferentiated tumor relation develops epidemiologically. Cervical node metastasis occurs clinically commonly.<br><br>Standard pathology: EBV infects epithelial cells and contributes to oncogenic transformation symptomatically. Serologic markers may aid diagnosis.<br><br>HPV (option A), cytomegalovirus (option C), herpes simplex virus (option D), and influenza virus (option E) show weaker associations. Therefore EBV remains classically linked.<br><br><em>(Robbins Basic Pathology)</em>"},
  {q:"The commonest presenting symptom of nasopharyngeal carcinoma in recalls is:",o:["Dysphagia","Hoarseness","Vertigo","Neck swelling","Facial swelling"],a:3,e:"Neck swelling fits the commonest presenting symptom of nasopharyngeal carcinoma because cervical metastasis occurs early. Nasal symptoms develop clinically later in many cases.<br><br>Standard pathology: rich nasopharyngeal lymphatic drainage promotes nodal spread symptomatically. Jugulodigastric nodes commonly enlarge.<br><br>Dysphagia (option A), vertigo (option C), hoarseness (option B), and facial swelling (option E) are less frequent initial presentations. Therefore neck mass commonly appears first.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A teenage male presents with recurrent profuse epistaxis and nasal obstruction. Examination reveals a vascular nasopharyngeal mass. The diagnosis is most likely:",o:["Nasopharyngeal carcinoma","Antrochoanal polyp","Juvenile nasopharyngeal angiofibroma","Adenoid hypertrophy","Inverted papilloma"],a:2,e:"Juvenile nasopharyngeal angiofibroma fits adolescent males with recurrent severe epistaxis and nasal obstruction. Facial swelling develops clinically in advanced disease.<br><br>Standard pathology: highly vascular benign tumor arises near sphenopalatine foramen symptomatically. Biopsy is contraindicated because of bleeding risk.<br><br>Nasopharyngeal carcinoma (option A), antrochoanal polyp (option B), adenoid hypertrophy (option D), and inverted papilloma (option E) are less characteristic. Therefore angiofibroma is likely.<br><br><em>(Recall and Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common benign tumor of nasopharynx in adolescent males is:",o:["Fibroma","Hemangioma","Papilloma","Juvenile nasopharyngeal angiofibroma","Lipoma"],a:3,e:"Juvenile nasopharyngeal angiofibroma fits the commonest benign nasopharyngeal tumor in adolescent males. Severe epistaxis develops clinically characteristically.<br><br>Standard pathology: fibrovascular tumor originates near superior margin of sphenopalatine foramen symptomatically. Hormonal influences may contribute.<br><br>Fibroma (option A), papilloma (option C), hemangioma (option B), and lipoma (option E) occur less commonly. Therefore angiofibroma predominates.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"Biopsy is contraindicated in juvenile nasopharyngeal angiofibroma because of risk of:",o:["CSF leak","Air embolism","Malignant transformation","Facial palsy","Profuse hemorrhage"],a:4,e:"Profuse hemorrhage fits the reason biopsy is contraindicated in juvenile nasopharyngeal angiofibroma. Severe epistaxis develops clinically due to marked vascularity.<br><br>Standard pathology: tumor contains abundant thin-walled vessels lacking muscular support symptomatically. Imaging usually establishes diagnosis safely.<br><br>CSF leak (option A), air embolism (option B), facial palsy (option D), and malignant transformation (option C) are less immediate concerns. Therefore hemorrhage risk prevents biopsy.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The investigation of choice for evaluating extent of juvenile nasopharyngeal angiofibroma is:",o:["Plain X-ray skull","CT scan with contrast","Tympanometry","Pure tone audiometry","Barium swallow"],a:1,e:"Contrast-enhanced CT scan fits the preferred investigation for juvenile nasopharyngeal angiofibroma extent assessment. Bone erosion develops clinically in advanced tumors.<br><br>Standard radiology: CT demonstrates vascular mass and skull base extension symptomatically. MRI may complement soft tissue evaluation.<br><br>Plain skull X-ray (option A), tympanometry (option C), audiometry (option D), and barium swallow (option E) inadequately define disease extent. Therefore contrast CT is preferred.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with nasopharyngeal carcinoma develops diplopia due to involvement of:",o:["Olfactory nerve","Optic nerve","Cranial nerves in cavernous sinus","Facial nerve only","Hypoglossal nerve"],a:2,e:"Cranial nerves within cavernous sinus fit diplopia associated with advanced nasopharyngeal carcinoma. Skull base invasion develops clinically in advanced disease.<br><br>Standard anatomy: tumor extension may involve cranial nerves III, IV, and VI symptomatically. Ophthalmoplegia and facial pain may occur.<br><br>Olfactory nerve (option A), optic nerve alone (option B), facial nerve only (option D), and hypoglossal nerve (option E) do not primarily explain diplopia. Therefore cavernous sinus involvement is likely.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"The hallmark symptom of juvenile nasopharyngeal angiofibroma is:",o:["Hyposmia","Tinnitus","Dysphagia","Recurrent epistaxis","Vertigo"],a:3,e:"Recurrent epistaxis fits the hallmark presentation of juvenile nasopharyngeal angiofibroma; characteristic vascularity causes repeated bleeding episodes. Nasal obstruction develops clinically additionally.<br><br>Standard pathology: fibrovascular tumor vessels bleed easily symptomatically. Progressive extension may deform facial structures.<br><br>Hyposmia (option A), dysphagia (option C), tinnitus (option B), and vertigo (option E) are less characteristic presentations. Therefore recurrent epistaxis strongly suggests angiofibroma.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The commonest route of spread of nasopharyngeal carcinoma is through:",o:["Bloodstream only","CSF pathways","Thoracic duct first","Direct tracheal spread","Lymphatics"],a:4,e:"Lymphatic spread fits the commonest dissemination route of nasopharyngeal carcinoma; characteristic cervical metastasis develops clinically early. Neck swelling often precedes nasal symptoms.<br><br>Standard anatomy: extensive nasopharyngeal lymphatic drainage promotes nodal spread symptomatically. Bilateral cervical nodes may occur.<br><br>Bloodstream only (option A), CSF pathways (option B), tracheal spread (option D), and thoracic duct-first spread (option C) are less typical. Therefore lymphatic dissemination predominates.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"The \"Holman-Miller sign\" is associated with:",o:["Nasopharyngeal carcinoma","Adenoid hypertrophy","Juvenile nasopharyngeal angiofibroma","Antrochoanal polyp","Ethmoidal carcinoma"],a:2,e:"Juvenile nasopharyngeal angiofibroma fits the Holman-Miller sign showing anterior bowing of posterior maxillary wall. Progressive nasal obstruction develops clinically commonly.<br><br>Standard radiology: expanding tumor within pterygopalatine fossa displaces maxillary sinus wall symptomatically. CT scan demonstrates this finding clearly.<br><br>Nasopharyngeal carcinoma (option A), adenoid hypertrophy (option B), antrochoanal polyp (option D), and ethmoidal carcinoma (option E) do not produce this classic sign. Therefore angiofibroma is correct.<br><br><em>(Recall and Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"The treatment of choice for juvenile nasopharyngeal angiofibroma is:",o:["Radiotherapy only","Chemotherapy","Steroid therapy","Observation only","Surgical excision"],a:4,e:"Surgical excision fits the treatment of choice for juvenile nasopharyngeal angiofibroma. Epistaxis improves clinically after complete tumor removal.<br><br>Standard management: preoperative embolization may reduce intraoperative bleeding symptomatically. Endoscopic approaches are increasingly preferred.<br><br>Radiotherapy alone (option A), chemotherapy (option B), observation only (option D), and steroids (option C) are not primary definitive treatments. Therefore surgery remains standard.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with unilateral conductive hearing loss and persistent middle ear effusion should be evaluated for:",o:["Otosclerosis only","Nasopharyngeal carcinoma","Ménière disease","Acoustic neuroma","Presbycusis"],a:1,e:"Nasopharyngeal carcinoma fits unilateral persistent middle ear effusion in adults due to Eustachian tube obstruction. Neck nodes develop clinically frequently.<br><br>Standard pathology: tumor near pharyngeal opening of auditory tube impairs middle ear ventilation symptomatically. Adult unilateral effusion requires exclusion of malignancy.<br><br>Otosclerosis (option A), Ménière disease (option C), acoustic neuroma (option D), and presbycusis (option E) less commonly cause this finding. Therefore nasopharyngeal carcinoma must be excluded.<br><br><em>(Recall and Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common age group affected by juvenile nasopharyngeal angiofibroma is:",o:["Neonates","Elderly adults","Infants","Middle-aged females","Adolescent males"],a:4,e:"Adolescent males fit the classic demographic for juvenile nasopharyngeal angiofibroma. Recurrent epistaxis develops clinically prominently.<br><br>Standard epidemiology: hormonal influences may contribute to tumor development symptomatically. Disease almost exclusively affects boys.<br><br>Neonates (option A), elderly adults (option B), middle-aged females (option D), and infants (option C) are rarely affected. Therefore adolescent males predominate.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The investigation most useful for confirming EBV association in nasopharyngeal carcinoma is:",o:["Serum calcium","Serum amylase","Mantoux test","Sweat chloride test","EBV serology"],a:4,e:"EBV serology fits confirmation of Epstein-Barr virus association with nasopharyngeal carcinoma. Cervical lymphadenopathy develops clinically early in disease.<br><br>Standard pathology: elevated EBV antibody titers correlate with undifferentiated nasopharyngeal carcinoma symptomatically. Viral markers aid screening in endemic regions.<br><br>Serum calcium (option A), Mantoux test (option C), sweat chloride test (option D), and serum amylase (option B) are unrelated investigations. Therefore EBV serology is useful.<br><br><em>(Robbins Basic Pathology)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common cranial nerve involved in advanced nasopharyngeal carcinoma is:",o:["Olfactory nerve","Optic nerve","Abducens nerve","Facial nerve","Hypoglossal nerve"],a:2,e:"Abducens nerve fits the commonest cranial nerve involved in advanced nasopharyngeal carcinoma. Diplopia develops clinically because lateral rectus muscle becomes weak.<br><br>Standard anatomy: skull base extension near cavernous sinus affects sixth cranial nerve symptomatically. Multiple cranial neuropathies may coexist.<br><br>Olfactory nerve (option A), optic nerve (option B), facial nerve (option D), and hypoglossal nerve (option E) are less commonly involved initially. Therefore abducens nerve involvement is classic.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A biopsy from nasopharyngeal carcinoma most commonly reveals:",o:["Basal cell carcinoma","Squamous cell carcinoma","Osteosarcoma","Fibroma","Chondroma"],a:1,e:"Squamous cell carcinoma fits the commonest histology identified in nasopharyngeal malignancy. Neck metastasis develops clinically early.<br><br>Standard pathology: keratinizing or nonkeratinizing squamous variants arise from nasopharyngeal mucosa symptomatically. Undifferentiated forms strongly associate with EBV.<br><br>Basal cell carcinoma (option A), osteosarcoma (option C), fibroma (option D), and chondroma (option E) occur rarely in nasopharynx. Therefore squamous carcinoma predominates histologically.<br><br><em>(Robbins Basic Pathology)</em>"},
  {q:"The blood supply of juvenile nasopharyngeal angiofibroma mainly arises from the:",o:["Internal carotid artery","Facial artery","Vertebral artery","Lingual artery","Internal maxillary artery"],a:4,e:"Internal maxillary artery fits the major vascular supply of juvenile nasopharyngeal angiofibroma. Severe intraoperative bleeding develops clinically because of vascularity.<br><br>Standard anatomy: branches such as sphenopalatine artery contribute significantly symptomatically. Preoperative embolization often targets these vessels.<br><br>Internal carotid artery (option A), facial artery (option B), lingual artery (option D), and vertebral artery (option C) are less important feeders. Therefore internal maxillary artery predominates.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with advanced nasopharyngeal carcinoma complains of facial pain and numbness. The most likely involved nerve is:",o:["Facial nerve","Trigeminal nerve","Glossopharyngeal nerve","Vagus nerve","Accessory nerve"],a:1,e:"Trigeminal nerve involvement fits facial pain and numbness in advanced nasopharyngeal carcinoma. Skull base extension develops clinically in late disease.<br><br>Standard anatomy: tumor may invade foramina near trigeminal pathways symptomatically. Sensory deficits and neuralgia-like pain may occur.<br><br>Facial nerve (option A), glossopharyngeal nerve (option C), vagus nerve (option D), and accessory nerve (option E) less commonly produce facial numbness. Therefore trigeminal involvement is likely.<br><br><em>(Recall and Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"The preferred treatment modality for nasopharyngeal carcinoma is:",o:["Surgery only","Tonsillectomy","Cryotherapy","Observation","Radiotherapy"],a:4,e:"Radiotherapy fits the preferred primary treatment for nasopharyngeal carcinoma because of deep anatomical location and radiosensitivity. Neck nodes regress clinically after therapy.<br><br>Standard oncology: chemoradiotherapy is frequently employed for advanced stages symptomatically. Surgery has limited primary role.<br><br>Surgery only (option A), cryotherapy (option C), observation (option D), and tonsillectomy (option B) are inappropriate definitive treatments. Therefore radiotherapy remains standard.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A young male with recurrent epistaxis and nasal obstruction undergoes imaging showing anterior bowing of posterior maxillary wall. Diagnosis is:",o:["Nasopharyngeal carcinoma","Ethmoidal polyp","Inverted papilloma","Adenoid hypertrophy","Juvenile nasopharyngeal angiofibroma"],a:4,e:"Juvenile nasopharyngeal angiofibroma fits recurrent epistaxis with Holman-Miller sign on imaging. Nasal obstruction develops clinically progressively.<br><br>Standard radiology: tumor expansion into pterygopalatine fossa displaces posterior maxillary wall symptomatically. Adolescent males remain predominantly affected.<br><br>Nasopharyngeal carcinoma (option A), ethmoidal polyp (option B), adenoid hypertrophy (option D), and inverted papilloma (option C) do not produce this sign. Therefore angiofibroma is likely.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"Bilateral cervical lymph node enlargement in a patient with nasal obstruction and serous otitis media strongly suggests:",o:["Allergic rhinitis","Septal deviation","Adenoid hypertrophy","Nasal vestibulitis","Nasopharyngeal carcinoma"],a:4,e:"Nasopharyngeal carcinoma fits bilateral cervical lymphadenopathy with unilateral middle ear effusion and nasal obstruction. Headache develops clinically in advanced disease.<br><br>Standard pathology: extensive lymphatic drainage from nasopharynx produces early nodal metastasis symptomatically. Adult unilateral effusion remains suspicious.<br><br>Allergic rhinitis (option A), adenoid hypertrophy (option C), nasal vestibulitis (option D), and septal deviation (option B) rarely produce metastatic neck nodes. Therefore carcinoma is strongly suggested.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"The most important preoperative step before surgery for juvenile nasopharyngeal angiofibroma is:",o:["Tonsillectomy","Tracheostomy","Preoperative embolization","Mastoidectomy","Septoplasty"],a:2,e:"Preoperative embolization fits the most important preparation before angiofibroma surgery because it reduces intraoperative hemorrhage. Blood loss develops clinically significantly without preparation.<br><br>Standard management: angiography identifies feeding vessels before embolization symptomatically. Surgical excision becomes safer afterward.<br><br>Tonsillectomy (option A), tracheostomy (option B), mastoidectomy (option D), and septoplasty (option E) are unrelated preparatory procedures. Therefore embolization is essential.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A 38-year-old man presents with unilateral nasal obstruction, blood-stained nasal discharge, persistent unilateral serous otitis media, and painless upper deep cervical lymphadenopathy. Nasal endoscopy reveals fullness in the fossa of Rosenmüller. The most likely diagnosis is:",o:["Antrochoanal polyp","Nasopharyngeal carcinoma","Juvenile nasopharyngeal angiofibroma","Thornwaldt cyst","Inverted papilloma"],a:1,e:"Nasopharyngeal carcinoma fits unilateral serous otitis media with cervical lymphadenopathy and fossa of Rosenmüller fullness. Blood-stained discharge develops clinically frequently.<br><br>Standard pathology: tumor obstructs Eustachian tube opening while spreading early through lymphatics symptomatically. Adult unilateral middle ear effusion is suspicious.<br><br>Antrochoanal polyp (option A), juvenile angiofibroma (option C), Thornwaldt cyst (option D), and inverted papilloma (option E) less commonly produce nodal metastasis. Therefore nasopharyngeal carcinoma is most likely.<br><br><em>(Recall and Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"The earliest cranial nerve palsy associated with skull base invasion in nasopharyngeal carcinoma most commonly involves:",o:["Facial nerve","Optic nerve","Hypoglossal nerve","Olfactory nerve","Abducens nerve"],a:4,e:"Abducens nerve fits the earliest cranial nerve involvement in skull base extension of nasopharyngeal carcinoma. Diplopia develops clinically because lateral rectus function weakens.<br><br>Standard anatomy: sixth cranial nerve traverses cavernous sinus and clivus region vulnerable to tumor invasion symptomatically. Headache frequently accompanies findings.<br><br>Facial nerve (option A), optic nerve (option B), olfactory nerve (option D), and hypoglossal nerve (option C) are less commonly affected initially. Therefore abducens palsy is classic.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A 16-year-old boy develops progressive unilateral nasal obstruction and recurrent torrential epistaxis requiring repeated admissions. CT scan shows anterior bowing of posterior maxillary wall. The most likely diagnosis is:",o:["Nasopharyngeal carcinoma","Ethmoidal polyp","Juvenile nasopharyngeal angiofibroma","Adenoid hypertrophy","Sinonasal melanoma"],a:2,e:"Juvenile nasopharyngeal angiofibroma fits adolescent males with severe recurrent epistaxis and Holman-Miller sign. Facial swelling develops clinically in advanced disease.<br><br>Standard pathology: highly vascular fibrovascular tumor arises near sphenopalatine foramen symptomatically. Biopsy risks catastrophic bleeding.<br><br>Nasopharyngeal carcinoma (option A), ethmoidal polyp (option B), adenoid hypertrophy (option D), and melanoma (option E) are less characteristic. Therefore angiofibroma is correct.<br><br><em>(Recall and Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The strongest epidemiological association with endemic nasopharyngeal carcinoma is consumption of:",o:["Citrus fruits","Smoked salted fish","Dairy products","Red meat only","Wheat products"],a:1,e:"Smoked salted fish fits the strongest dietary association with endemic nasopharyngeal carcinoma. Nitrosamine exposure develops clinically important carcinogenic effects.<br><br>Standard epidemiology: chronic dietary carcinogen exposure combined with Epstein-Barr virus predisposes susceptible populations symptomatically. Southeast Asian prevalence remains high.<br><br>Citrus fruits (option A), dairy products (option C), red meat alone (option D), and wheat products (option E) lack similar established association. Therefore salted fish exposure is important.<br><br><em>(Recall and Robbins Basic Pathology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with advanced nasopharyngeal carcinoma develops severe facial pain, numbness over cheek, and absent corneal reflex. The involved cranial nerve is:",o:["Facial nerve","Trigeminal nerve","Glossopharyngeal nerve","Accessory nerve","Vagus nerve"],a:1,e:"Trigeminal nerve involvement fits facial numbness and absent corneal reflex in advanced nasopharyngeal carcinoma. Skull base infiltration develops clinically in late disease.<br><br>Standard anatomy: tumor extension through foramina may affect trigeminal sensory branches symptomatically. Neuralgic facial pain commonly accompanies findings.<br><br>Facial nerve (option A), glossopharyngeal nerve (option C), accessory nerve (option D), and vagus nerve (option E) do not primarily mediate corneal sensation. Therefore trigeminal nerve is affected.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"The investigation most useful for staging skull base extension in nasopharyngeal carcinoma is:",o:["Plain X-ray skull","Water's view X-ray","Tympanometry","PET scan only","MRI"],a:4,e:"MRI fits the best investigation for assessing skull base and intracranial extension in nasopharyngeal carcinoma. Cranial neuropathies develop clinically with advanced spread.<br><br>Standard radiology: MRI provides superior soft tissue and neural detail symptomatically. Perineural spread becomes more accurately visualized.<br><br>Plain skull X-ray (option A), tympanometry (option C), PET scan alone (option D), and Water's view X-ray (option B) are less informative for skull base invasion. Therefore MRI is preferred.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 14-year-old boy undergoes attempted biopsy of a vascular nasopharyngeal mass and develops massive hemorrhage. Histology was most likely unnecessary because the lesion classically is:",o:["Lymphoma","Juvenile nasopharyngeal angiofibroma","Nasopharyngeal carcinoma","Chordoma","Rhabdomyosarcoma"],a:1,e:"Juvenile nasopharyngeal angiofibroma fits catastrophic hemorrhage after biopsy because of extreme vascularity. Adolescent males develop clinically recurrent epistaxis characteristically.<br><br>Standard pathology: diagnosis is usually radiologic rather than histologic symptomatically. Biopsy risks uncontrollable bleeding.<br><br>Lymphoma (option A), nasopharyngeal carcinoma (option C), chordoma (option D), and rhabdomyosarcoma (option E) are not classically biopsy-prohibited vascular lesions. Therefore angiofibroma is correct.<br><br><em>(Recall and Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The commonest route of metastasis in nasopharyngeal carcinoma is to:",o:["Liver directly","Brain tissue","Lungs first","Vertebral column","Cervical lymph nodes"],a:4,e:"Cervical lymph nodes fit the commonest metastatic site in nasopharyngeal carcinoma. Neck swelling develops clinically before primary symptoms frequently.<br><br>Standard pathology: abundant nasopharyngeal lymphatics facilitate early nodal dissemination symptomatically. Bilateral nodal involvement may occur.<br><br>Direct liver spread (option A), lungs first (option C), vertebral metastasis (option D), and brain tissue spread (option B) are later events. Therefore cervical nodes are first involved.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient presents with conductive deafness, persistent unilateral middle ear effusion, and headache. Otoscopy reveals intact tympanic membrane. Which diagnosis must be excluded first?",o:["Ménière disease","Otosclerosis","Nasopharyngeal carcinoma","Presbycusis","Labyrinthitis"],a:2,e:"Nasopharyngeal carcinoma fits unilateral adult middle ear effusion with headache and conductive hearing loss. Eustachian tube obstruction develops clinically commonly.<br><br>Standard pathology: tumors near pharyngeal tubal opening impair middle ear ventilation symptomatically. Adult unilateral glue ear requires urgent nasopharyngeal evaluation.<br><br>Ménière disease (option A), otosclerosis (option B), presbycusis (option D), and labyrinthitis (option E) less commonly produce unilateral effusion. Therefore carcinoma must be excluded.<br><br><em>(Recall and Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The characteristic imaging feature of juvenile nasopharyngeal angiofibroma on CT is:",o:["Onion skin appearance","Cotton wool skull","Tram-track calcification","Ground glass opacity","Anterior bowing of posterior maxillary wall"],a:4,e:"Anterior bowing of posterior maxillary wall fits the Holman-Miller sign of juvenile nasopharyngeal angiofibroma. Progressive nasal obstruction develops clinically characteristically.<br><br>Standard radiology: tumor extension into pterygopalatine fossa displaces maxillary sinus wall symptomatically. Contrast enhancement is usually intense.<br><br>Onion skin appearance (option A), cotton wool skull (option B), ground glass opacity (option D), and tram-track calcification (option C) belong to unrelated conditions. Therefore Holman-Miller sign is classic.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"The most radiosensitive head and neck malignancy among nasopharyngeal tumors is:",o:["Fibrosarcoma","Chondrosarcoma","Nasopharyngeal carcinoma","Osteoma","Papilloma"],a:2,e:"Nasopharyngeal carcinoma fits the most radiosensitive malignant nasopharyngeal tumor. Primary radiotherapy develops clinically as standard treatment.<br><br>Standard oncology: anatomical inaccessibility and radiosensitivity make nonsurgical treatment preferable symptomatically. Chemoradiotherapy improves survival in advanced disease.<br><br>Fibrosarcoma (option A), chondrosarcoma (option B), osteoma (option D), and papilloma (option E) are not treated primarily with radiotherapy. Therefore nasopharyngeal carcinoma is highly radiosensitive.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with nasopharyngeal carcinoma develops deviation of tongue to one side. Which cranial nerve involvement explains this?",o:["Facial nerve","Trigeminal nerve","Accessory nerve","Vagus nerve","Hypoglossal nerve"],a:4,e:"Hypoglossal nerve involvement fits tongue deviation in advanced nasopharyngeal carcinoma. Skull base invasion develops clinically in extensive disease.<br><br>Standard anatomy: twelfth cranial nerve controls ipsilateral tongue muscles symptomatically. Weakness causes deviation toward affected side.<br><br>Facial nerve (option A), trigeminal nerve (option B), vagus nerve (option D), and accessory nerve (option C) do not directly control tongue protrusion. Therefore hypoglossal palsy explains findings.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A 17-year-old male presents with unilateral proptosis, recurrent epistaxis, and nasal obstruction. The most likely mechanism for proptosis is:",o:["Cavernous sinus thrombosis","Intracranial hemorrhage","Maxillary cyst rupture","Facial nerve paralysis","Extension of juvenile angiofibroma into orbit"],a:4,e:"Orbital extension of juvenile angiofibroma fits proptosis in adolescent males with severe epistaxis. Facial deformity develops clinically in extensive disease.<br><br>Standard pathology: aggressive local expansion through pterygopalatine and infratemporal fossae may reach orbit symptomatically. Bone remodeling frequently occurs.<br><br>Cavernous sinus thrombosis (option A), intracranial hemorrhage (option B), facial palsy (option D), and cyst rupture (option C) are less characteristic explanations. Therefore orbital extension is likely.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"The preferred definitive diagnosis of nasopharyngeal carcinoma is established by:",o:["FNAC of neck node only","Plain X-ray skull","Endoscopic biopsy","Tympanometry","Audiometry"],a:2,e:"Endoscopic biopsy fits the definitive diagnostic method for nasopharyngeal carcinoma. Histopathologic confirmation develops clinically before treatment planning.<br><br>Standard ENT evaluation: endoscopy visualizes suspicious lesions within nasopharynx symptomatically. Directed biopsy confirms malignancy.<br><br>FNAC alone (option A), skull radiography (option B), tympanometry (option D), and audiometry (option E) cannot establish definitive histology. Therefore endoscopic biopsy is required.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"Which nasopharyngeal tumor is most strongly associated with adolescent males and testosterone sensitivity?",o:["Nasopharyngeal carcinoma","Juvenile nasopharyngeal angiofibroma","Lymphoma","Chordoma","Adenoid cystic carcinoma"],a:1,e:"Juvenile nasopharyngeal angiofibroma fits the androgen-sensitive vascular tumor affecting adolescent males. Severe epistaxis develops clinically repeatedly.<br><br>Standard pathology: hormonal receptor influence likely contributes to disease predominance symptomatically. Growth often stabilizes after adolescence.<br><br>Nasopharyngeal carcinoma (option A), lymphoma (option C), chordoma (option D), and adenoid cystic carcinoma (option E) lack this characteristic hormonal association. Therefore angiofibroma is correct.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with nasopharyngeal carcinoma presents with trismus. The most likely anatomical structure involved is the:",o:["Buccinator muscle","Platysma muscle","Orbicularis oris","Cricopharyngeus muscle","Medial pterygoid muscle"],a:4,e:"Medial pterygoid involvement fits trismus associated with advanced nasopharyngeal carcinoma. Infratemporal fossa extension develops clinically in locally advanced disease.<br><br>Standard anatomy: tumor spread into pterygoid musculature restricts mandibular movement symptomatically. Painful mouth opening commonly occurs.<br><br>Buccinator (option A), orbicularis oris (option C), cricopharyngeus (option D), and platysma (option B) are less relevant to trismus. Therefore medial pterygoid involvement is likely.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common histological subtype of endemic nasopharyngeal carcinoma is:",o:["Keratinizing squamous carcinoma","Adenocarcinoma","Basal cell carcinoma","Verrucous carcinoma","Non-keratinizing undifferentiated carcinoma"],a:4,e:"Non-keratinizing undifferentiated carcinoma fits the common endemic histological subtype associated strongly with Epstein-Barr virus. Cervical node metastasis develops clinically early.<br><br>Standard pathology: poorly differentiated malignant epithelial cells characterize this variant symptomatically. Radiosensitivity remains relatively high.<br><br>Keratinizing squamous carcinoma (option A), basal cell carcinoma (option C), verrucous carcinoma (option D), and adenocarcinoma (option B) occur less commonly. Therefore undifferentiated carcinoma predominates in endemic areas.<br><br><em>(Robbins Basic Pathology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with juvenile nasopharyngeal angiofibroma undergoes preoperative embolization mainly to reduce:",o:["CSF leak","Tumor recurrence","Intraoperative bleeding","Facial nerve injury","Airway edema"],a:2,e:"Intraoperative bleeding reduction fits the main goal of embolization before angiofibroma surgery. Surgical visualization improves clinically after vascular control.<br><br>Standard management: feeding vessels from internal maxillary artery are selectively embolized symptomatically. Blood transfusion requirements decrease.<br><br>CSF leak (option A), recurrence prevention alone (option B), facial nerve injury (option D), and airway edema (option E) are not primary indications. Therefore hemorrhage control is essential.<br><br><em>(Recall and Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A middle-aged patient presents with unilateral conductive hearing loss, nasal speech, diplopia, and sixth nerve palsy. The primary lesion is most likely located in the:",o:["Oropharynx","Nasopharynx","Middle ear","Maxillary sinus","External auditory canal"],a:1,e:"Nasopharyngeal lesion fits unilateral conductive hearing loss with sixth nerve palsy and nasal symptoms. Skull base involvement develops clinically in advanced carcinoma.<br><br>Standard pathology: tumor near Eustachian tube causes middle ear effusion while cavernous sinus extension affects abducens nerve symptomatically. Diplopia becomes characteristic.<br><br>Oropharynx (option A), middle ear (option C), maxillary sinus (option D), and external canal (option E) less commonly explain combined findings. Therefore nasopharynx is implicated.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"The principal arterial feeder of juvenile nasopharyngeal angiofibroma most commonly arises from the:",o:["Internal carotid artery","Facial artery","Superior thyroid artery","Lingual artery","Internal maxillary artery"],a:4,e:"Internal maxillary artery fits the major arterial feeder supplying juvenile nasopharyngeal angiofibroma. Recurrent epistaxis develops clinically from vascularity.<br><br>Standard anatomy: sphenopalatine and descending palatine branches contribute significantly symptomatically. Angiography identifies feeding vessels preoperatively.<br><br>Internal carotid artery (option A), facial artery (option B), lingual artery (option D), and superior thyroid artery (option C) are less important sources. Therefore internal maxillary artery predominates.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"Which symptom combination is considered highly suspicious for nasopharyngeal carcinoma in FCPS recall patterns?",o:["Bilateral tinnitus with vertigo","Adult unilateral serous otitis media with neck node","Hoarseness with hemoptysis","Sneezing with watery rhinorrhea","Recurrent tonsillitis with fever"],a:1,e:"Adult unilateral serous otitis media with cervical node enlargement fits a classic suspicious pattern for nasopharyngeal carcinoma. Nasal obstruction develops clinically later.<br><br>Standard pathology: Eustachian tube blockage combined with lymphatic metastasis produces this presentation symptomatically. Persistent unilateral glue ear in adults warrants nasopharyngeal evaluation.<br><br>Bilateral tinnitus with vertigo (option A), hoarseness (option C), allergic symptoms (option D), and tonsillitis (option E) are less specific. Therefore unilateral effusion with neck node is highly suspicious.<br><br><em>(Recall and Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with advanced nasopharyngeal carcinoma develops severe headache due to invasion of:",o:["External auditory canal","Thyroid cartilage","Hard palate","Vocal cords","Skull base"],a:4,e:"Skull base invasion fits severe headache associated with advanced nasopharyngeal carcinoma. Cranial neuropathies develop clinically with progressive extension.<br><br>Standard pathology: tumor infiltration of clivus and adjacent foramina irritates pain-sensitive structures symptomatically. Intracranial spread may occur.<br><br>External auditory canal (option A), hard palate (option C), vocal cords (option D), and thyroid cartilage (option B) are less likely sources of severe headache. Therefore skull base involvement is responsible.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"The most appropriate primary treatment for advanced-stage nasopharyngeal carcinoma is:",o:["Surgery alone","Radiotherapy with chemotherapy","Cryosurgery","Adenoidectomy","Laser cauterization"],a:1,e:"Combined radiotherapy and chemotherapy fits standard treatment for advanced nasopharyngeal carcinoma. Cervical metastases respond clinically better with combined modalities.<br><br>Standard oncology: concurrent chemoradiation improves locoregional control and survival symptomatically. Surgery has limited primary role because of anatomical constraints.<br><br>Surgery alone (option A), cryosurgery (option C), adenoidectomy (option D), and laser cauterization (option E) are inadequate definitive therapies. Therefore chemoradiotherapy is preferred.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A young boy with recurrent epistaxis has a vascular nasopharyngeal tumor extending into pterygopalatine fossa. The most likely diagnosis is:",o:["Chordoma","Nasopharyngeal carcinoma","Lymphoma","Ethmoidal carcinoma","Juvenile nasopharyngeal angiofibroma"],a:4,e:"Juvenile nasopharyngeal angiofibroma fits vascular nasopharyngeal tumors extending into pterygopalatine fossa. Severe epistaxis develops clinically repeatedly.<br><br>Standard pathology: locally aggressive fibrovascular growth spreads through natural skull base pathways symptomatically. CT commonly demonstrates characteristic extension patterns.<br><br>Chordoma (option A), nasopharyngeal carcinoma (option B), ethmoidal carcinoma (option D), and lymphoma (option C) less commonly produce this classic adolescent presentation. Therefore angiofibroma is correct.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"Bilateral neck node metastases are especially characteristic of:",o:["Adenoid hypertrophy","Juvenile angiofibroma","Nasopharyngeal carcinoma","Thornwaldt cyst","Antrochoanal polyp"],a:2,e:"Nasopharyngeal carcinoma fits bilateral cervical node metastases because of extensive bilateral lymphatic drainage. Neck swelling develops clinically early in disease.<br><br>Standard pathology: lymphatic dissemination often precedes obvious primary tumor symptoms symptomatically. Jugulodigastric nodes commonly enlarge first.<br><br>Adenoid hypertrophy (option A), juvenile angiofibroma (option B), Thornwaldt cyst (option D), and antrochoanal polyp (option E) are benign lesions without metastatic behavior. Therefore carcinoma is characteristic.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
];